isit_heard_island|title=Frequently asked questions|first=c=AU;o=Commonwealth of Australia;ou=Department of the Environment and Energy;ou=Australian Antarctic|last=Division|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.npolar.no/en/antarctica/peter-I-oy.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=May 12, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017215217/http://www.npolar.no/en/antarctica/peter-I-oy.html |archivedate=October 17, 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.npolar.no/en/antarctica/dronning-maud-land.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=August 20, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017215832/http://www.npolar.no/en/antarctica/dronning-maud-land.html |archivedate=October 17, 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mfat.govt.nz/Foreign-Relations/Antarctica/3-New-Zealand-Procedures-for-Visitors-to-Antarctica/index.php|title=The Ministry of Foreign Affairs and Trade acts in the world to make New Zealanders safer and more prosperous|first=New Zealand Ministry of Foreign Affairs and|last=Trade|website=New Zealand Ministry of Foreign Affairs and Trade}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Passport card==\nThe [[United States Passport Card]] can be used as an alternative to the passport booklet only when travelling to and from Canada, Mexico, Bermuda, and Caribbean islands at maritime [[Port of entry|ports-of-entry]] or land border crossings. The card is not valid for air travel whatsoever; if traveling by air, the passport book is required.<ref>state.gov: [https://travel.state.gov/content/passports/english/passports/information/card.html Passport Card] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150905084744/http://travel.state.gov/content/passports/english/passports/information/card.html# |date=2015-09-05 }}, accessdate: June 6, 2015</ref>\n\n==APEC Travel Business Card==\nThe [[APEC Business Travel Card]] (ABTC) is meant to facilitate travel for U.S. citizens engaged in verified business in the [[APEC]] region.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbp.gov/travel/trusted-traveler-programs/us-apec-business-travel-card-program-frequently-asked-questions2|title=U.S. APEC Business Travel Card Program Frequently Asked Questions - U.S. Customs and Border Protection|access-date=2016-05-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160507203450/https://www.cbp.gov/travel/trusted-traveler-programs/us-apec-business-travel-card-program-frequently-asked-questions2#|archive-date=2016-05-07|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe U.S. [[APEC Business Travel Card|ABTC]] should enable access to a dedicated fast-track lane for expedited immigration processing at some participating foreign [[APEC]] member airports.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://travel.apec.org/abtc-summary.html|title=ABTC Summary  - APEC Business Travel Card|access-date=2018-04-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161019010749/http://travel.apec.org/abtc-summary.html|archive-date=2016-10-19|url-status=dead}}</ref> U.S. APEC Business Travel Card holders may also use the Global Entry kiosks at participating airports upon their U.S. return.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbp.gov/travel/trusted-traveler-programs/global-entry/locations|title=Airports with Global Entry Kiosks - U.S. Customs and Border Protection|publisher=}}</ref> However, the U.S. APEC Business Travel Card cannot be used in lieu of a visa to enter an APEC member country in the way that some other countries\u2019 APEC cards can be used in lieu of visas. This is because the U.S. has decided not to participate in the visa reciprocity part of the program because the US government is unwilling to waive visa interviews.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lawandborder.com/does-a-u-s-apec-business-traveler-card-allow-visa-free-travel-to-china/|title=Does a U.S. APEC Business Travel Card Allow Visa-Free Travel to China? - Chodorow Law Offices|date=13 December 2015|publisher=}}</ref> The program was initially set to expire on 30 September 2018, but the November 2017 signing of the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation Business Travel Cards Act of 2017 (S. 504) ensured it would permanently remain.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/115th-congress/senate-bill/504|title=S.504 - Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation Business Travel Cards Act of 2017|work=[[Congress.gov]]|accessdate=12 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Consular protection of U.S. citizens abroad==\n[[File:US embassies 2007.png|thumb|upright=3.2|center|American diplomatic missions (in the year 2007), including embassies (blue), interests sections, and other representations (light blue)]]\nThe United States has the most diplomatic missions of any country in the world.\n<br>\nSee also [[List of diplomatic missions of the United States]].\n\nThe [[Department of State]] regularly publishes '''travel warnings''' or '''travel alerts.'''\n\n==Non-visa restrictions==\n{{Transcluded section|Non-visa travel restrictions}}{{#section-h:Non-visa travel restrictions|List of common non-visa travel restrictions}}\n\n==Foreign travel statistics==\n{{transcluded section|source=United States passport}}\n{{trim|{{#section-h::United States passport|Foreign travel statistics}}}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|United States}}\n\n* [[Visa policy of the United States]]\n* [[United States passport]]\n* [[Bureau of Consular Affairs]]\n* [[United States Passport Card]]\n* [[List of nationalities forbidden at border]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|30em|group=\"Note\"}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://travel.state.gov/content/passports/english/country.html Official U.S. Government database], Bureau of Consular Affairs, U.S. Department of State\n\n{{Visa Requirements}}\n{{Visa policy by country}}\n\n[[Category:Visa requirements by nationality|United States of America]]\n[[Category:Foreign relations of the United States]]\n", "text_old": " [[File:Us-passport.jpg|thumb|A [[United States passport]] with biometric chip.]]\n'''Visa requirements for [[United States citizen]]s''' and '''[[U.S. national|non-citizen nationals]]''' are administrative entry restrictions by the authorities of [[Sovereign state|other states]] placed on citizens of the United States.\n\n{{As of|2020|04|07|post=,}} holders of a [[United States passport]] could travel to 185 countries and territories without a [[travel visa]], or with a visa on arrival. The [[United States passport]] currently ranks{{refn|group=Note|name=Ranking| Using [[Ranking#Dense ranking (\"1223\" ranking)|dense ranking]].}} 8th in terms of travel freedom (tied with the passports of Belgium, Switzerland, Norway and the UK) according to the [[Henley Passport Index]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Global Ranking \u2013 Visa Passport Index|url=https://www.henleypassportindex.com/assets/2020/Q1/2020%20HPI%20and%20Global%20Mobility%20Report_200107.pdf|publisher=Henley & Partners|accessdate=7 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==2020 travel restrictions==\n{{main|Travel restrictions related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n[[File:USA Travel Restrictions from COVID-19.svg|thumb|600px|Countries that have imposed some form of travel restrictions on US Citizens and/or travel from the United States]]\nAs a result of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], several countries have imposed temporary travel restrictions on United States citizens or persons arriving from the United States.<ref name=\"IATA\">[https://www.iatatravelcentre.com/international-travel-document-news/1580226297.htm CORONAVIRUS OUTBREAK IN CHINA (PEOPLE'S REP.) - UPDATE], International Air Transport Association Travel Centre</ref>\n*{{flag|Argentina}} \u2014 Admission refused, except residents.\n*{{flag|Austria}} \u2014 Admission to [[Schengen Area]] refused from noon 17 March until April 30, except residents, family members of EU citizens, medical personnel, and people responsible for transport of goods.\n*{{flag|Australia}} \u2014 Admission suspended for non Australians except for Family connection\n*{{flag|Belgium}} \u2014 Admission to [[Schengen Area]] refused from noon 17 March until April 30, except residents, family members of EU citizens, medical personnel, and people responsible for transport of goods.\n*{{flag|Bermuda}} \u2014 14-day self-quarantine required.\n*{{flag|Botswana}} \u2014 Admission refused.\n*{{flag|Brazil}} \u2014 Admission suspended for non Brazilians except for Family connection.\n*{{flag|Brunei}} \u2014 Admission refused.\n*{{flag|Cambodia}} \u2014 Admission refused.\n*{{flag|Canada}} \u2014 Admission refused for nonessential travel.\n*{{flag|Chile}} \u2014 Admission refused for nonessential travel.\n*{{flag|Croatia}} \u2014 Admission refused for nonresidents.\n*{{flag|Cyprus}} \u2014 Admission refused with few exceptions until April 10.<ref>https://cy.usembassy.gov/covid-19-information/</ref>\n*{{flag|Colombia}} \u2014 Admission refused, except residents who perform an obligatory 14-day period of self isolation.\n*{{flag|Costa Rica}} \u2014 Admission refused until April 30, except residents, who are subject to mandatory 14-day quarantine.<ref>https://cr.usembassy.gov/covid-19-information/</ref>\n*{{flag|Czech Republic}} \u2014 Admission refused.\n*{{flag|Denmark}} \u2014 Admission to [[Schengen Area]] refused from noon 17 March until April 30, except residents, family members of EU citizens, medical personnel, and people responsible for transport of goods. Entry refused into Greenland and Faroe Islands until April 13.\n*{{flag|El Salvador}} \u2014 Admission refused, except accredited diplomats and legal residents.\n*{{flag|Estonia}} \u2014 Admission refused effective March 17. Right of entry will remain for citizens and those with a right of residence, as well as foreign citizens whose next of kin live in Estonia. Transit is allowed for foreigners not showing signs of the coronavirus. A mandatory two-week quarantine will be set for anyone entering the country.\n*{{flag|France}} \u2014 Admission to [[Schengen Area]] refused from noon 17 March until April 30, except residents, family members of EU citizens, medical personnel, and people responsible for transport of goods.\n*{{flag|Georgia (country)}} - Admission refused until April 21st, except dependents of citizens and diplomats.\n*{{flag|Germany}} \u2014 Admission to [[Schengen Area]] refused from noon 17 March until April 30, except residents, family members of EU citizens, medical personnel, and people responsible for transport of goods.\n*{{flag|Greece}} \u2014 Admission to [[Schengen Area]] refused from noon 17 March until April 30, except residents, family members of EU citizens, medical personnel, and people responsible for transport of goods.\n*{{flag|Guatemala}} \u2014 Admission refused.\n*{{flag|Hong Kong}} \u2014 Admission refused for nonessential travel.\n*{{flag|Honduras}} \u2014 Admission refused.<ref>https://hn.usembassy.gov/covid-19-information/</ref>\n*{{flag|Hungary}} \u2014 Admission refused.\n*{{flag|Iceland}} \u2014 Admission to [[Schengen Area]] refused from noon 17 March until April 30, except residents, family members of EU citizens, medical personnel, and people responsible for transport of goods.\n*{{flag|India}} \u2014 Admission refused.\n*{{flag|Indonesia}} \u2014 Admission refused.\n*{{flag|Italy}} \u2014 Admission to [[Schengen Area]] refused from noon 17 March until April 30, except residents, family members of EU citizens, medical personnel, and people responsible for transport of goods.\n*{{flag|Israel}} \u2014 Admission refused, except by specific permit for non-residents. All entrants must remain under home isolation for 14 days.\n*{{flag|Latvia}} \u2014 Admission to [[Schengen Area]] refused from noon 17 March until April 30, except residents, family members of EU citizens, medical personnel, and people responsible for transport of goods.\n*{{flag|Liechtenstein}} \u2014 Admission to [[Schengen Area]] refused from noon 17 March until April 30, except residents, family members of EU citizens, medical personnel, and people responsible for transport of goods.\n*{{flag|Lithuania}} \u2014 Admiss