Group<ref name=635SCOWfacts/>\n|}\n\n==References==\n\n===Notes===\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{Air Force Historical Research Agency}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.Scott.af.mil/ Scott AFB Home Page]\n\n{{USAF Material Command}}\n{{US Air Force navbox}}\n\n[[Category:Military units and formations in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Wings of the United States Air Force|0635]]\n[[Category:Logistics units and formations of the United States Air Force]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 2010]]\n", "text_old": "{{more footnotes|date=January 2013}}\n{{Infobox military unit\n|unit_name=635th Supply Chain Operations Wing\n|image= \n|caption=\n|dates=1966-1976; 2008-present\n|country=[[United States]]\n|branch=[[United States Air Force|Air Force]]\n|type=Logistics Operations\n|command_structure=[[Air Force Sustainment Center]]\n|current_commander= Col Robert Henderson\n|garrison=[[Scott Air Force Base]]\n|nickname=Smiling Bulls\n|motto= \"One call\" \n|mascot=Tigers\n|decorations=[[Air Force Outstanding Unit Award]] w/[[Combat \"V\" Device]] [[Gallantry Cross (Vietnam)|Vietnamese Gallantry Cross with Palm]]\n|notable_commanders=[https://www.af.mil/About-Us/Biographies/Display/Article/108893/major-general-mark-k-johnson/ Col Mark K. Johnson]\n|anniversaries=9 Apr\n<!-- Insignia -->\n|identification_symbol=[[File:635SCOW.jpg|175px]]\n|identification_symbol_label=635th Supply Chain Operations Wing emblem (approved 7 March 1968)<ref name=635SCOWfacts>{{cite web |url=http://www.afhra.af.mil/About-Us/Fact-Sheets/Display/Article/432534/635-supply-chain-operations-wing-afmc/ |last1=Robertson|first1=Patsy|title=Factsheet 635 Supply Chain Operations Wing (AFMC)|date=December 8, 2010|publisher=Air Force Historical Research Agency|url-status=live |accessdate=May 5, 2014}}</ref><ref>Revised 26 August 2010 to put current unit designation on scroll.</ref>\n|identification_symbol_2=\n|identification_symbol_2_label=\n}}\n\nThe '''635th Supply Chain Operations Wing''', [[United States Air Force]], is a logistics [[wing (air force unit)|wing]]. It reports to the [[Air Force Sustainment Center]], part of [[Air Force Materiel Command]], and serves as the Air Force's new supply chain manager headquartered at [[Scott Air Force Base]], [[Illinois]]. It is an associate tenant at the base.\n\n==History==\nThe wing was originally activated at [[U-Tapao Royal Thai Navy Airfield]] in June 1966<ref name=635SCOWfacts/> as the [[Pacific Air Forces]] support organization for operations from the base, primarily the [[Strategic Air Command]] Young Tiger Task Force.\n\nActivated as the headquarters for the Mobility Air Forces Logistics Support Center (redesignated 635th Supply Chain Management Group) and the Combat Air Forces Logistics Support Center (redesignated 735th Supply Chain Management Group) in 2008.\n\nIts units now include the:\n* 635th Supply Chain Operations Group, [[Scott Air Force Base]], Illinois\n* 735th Supply Chain Operations Group, [[Langley Air Force Base]], Virginia\n* 635th Materiel Maintenance Group, [[Holloman Air Force Base]], New Mexico\n* Detachment 1, Air Force Petroleum Office, [[Ft. Belvoir]], Virginia\n\n==Lineage==\n* Constituted as the '''635th Combat Support Group''' on 17 May 1966 and activated (not organized)\n: Organized on 8 July 1966\n: Redesignated '''635th Aerospace Support Group''' on 30 January 1976\n: Inactivated on 20 June 1976\n* Redesignated '''635th Supply Chain Management Wing''' on 12 March 2008\n: Activated on 1 April 2008\n: Redesignated '''635th Supply Chain Operations Wing''' on 30 June 2010<ref name=635SCOWfacts/>\n\n===Assignments===\n* [[Pacific Air Forces]], 17 May 1966 (not organized)\n* [[Thirteenth Air Force]], 8 July 1966\n* [[17th Air Division]], 1 July 1975\n* Thirteenth Air Force, 1 January 1976 - 20 June 1976\n* [[Air Force Global Logistics Support Center]], 1 April 2008 (attached to Air Force Sustainment Center after 11 July 2012)\n* Air Force Sustainment Center, 1 October 2012 \u2013 present<ref name=635SCOWfacts/>\n\n===Stations===\n* U Tapao Royal Thai Navy Airfield, Thailand 8 July 1966 - 20 June 1976\n* [[Scott Air Force Base]], Illinois, 1 April 2008 \u2013 present<ref name=635SCOWfacts/>\n\n===Components===\n\n====Groups====\n* 635th Supply Chain Management Group (later 635th Supply Chain Operations Group), 1 April 2008 - \n* 735th Supply Chain Management Group (later 735th Supply Chain Operations Group), 1 April 2008 -\n\n====Squadrons====\n* 635th Air Police Squadron (later 635th Security Police Squadron), 8 July 1966 - 20 June 1976\n* 635th Civil Engineering Squadron, 8 July 1966 - 20 June 1976\n* 635th Munitions Maintenance Squadron, 15 May 1967 - 20 June 1976\n* 635th Services Squadron, 8 July 1966 - 28 February 1975\n* 635th Supply Squadron, 8 July 1966 - 20 June 1976\n\n====Other====\n* 11th USAF Dispensary (later 11th USAF Hospital), 8 July 1966 - 20 June 1976\n\n===Awards and campaigns===\n{{unit awards table\n|award_image1=AF OUA w/ v\n|award_name1=[[Air Force Outstanding Unit Award]] w/[[Combat \"V\" Device]]\n|award_date1=8 July 1966-30 June 1968\n|award_notes1=635th Combat Support Group<ref name=635SCOWfacts/>\n|award_image2=AF OUA w/ v\n|award_name2=Air Force Outstanding Unit Award w/Combat \"V\" Device\n|award_date2=1 January 1970-30 May 1971\n|award_notes2=635th Combat Support Group<ref name=635SCOWfacts/>\n|award_image3=AF OUA w/ v\n|award_name3=Air Force Outstanding Unit Award w/Combat \"V\" Device\n|award_date3=1 June 1971-31 May 1972\n|award_notes3=635th Combat Support Group<ref name=635SCOWfacts/>\n|award_image4=AF OUA w/ v\n|award_name4=Air Force Outstanding Unit Award w/Combat \"V\" Device\n|award_date4=1 June 1972-31 March 1973\n|award_notes4=635th Combat Support Group<ref name=635SCOWfacts/>\n|award_image5=AF OUA w/ v\n|award_name5=Air Force Outstanding Unit Award w/Combat \"V\" Device\n|award_date5=1 April 1973-31 March 1974\n|award_notes5=635th Combat Support Group<ref name=635SCOWfacts/>\n|award_image6=VGC\n|award_name6=[[Gallantry Cross (Vietnam)|Vietnamese Gallantry Cross with Palm]]\n|award_date6=8 July 1966-28 January 1973\n|award_notes6=635th Combat Support Group<ref name=635SCOWfacts/>\n|award_image7=VGC\n|award_name7=[[Gallantry Cross (Vietnam)|Vietnamese Gallantry Cross with Palm]]\n|award_date7=29 April 1975-30 April 1975\n|award_notes7=635th Combat Support Group<ref name=635SCOWfacts/>\n}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#efefef;\"\n! Campaign Streamer\n! Campaign\n! Dates\n! Notes\n|-\n|[[Image:Streamer VS.PNG|200px]]||Vietnam Air Offensive||29 June 1966 \u2013 8 March 1967||635th Combat Support Group<ref name=635SCOWfacts/>\n|-\n|[[Image:Streamer VS.PNG|200px]]||Vietnam Air Offensive, Phase II||9 March 1967 \u2013 31 March 1968||635th Combat Support Group<ref name=635SCOWfacts/>\n|-\n|[[Image:Streamer VS.PNG|200px]]||Vietnam Air Offensive, Phase III||1 April 1968 \u2013 31 October 1968||635th Combat Support Group<ref name=635SCOWfacts/>\n|-\n|[[Image:Streamer VS.PNG|200px]]||Vietnam Air Offensive, Phase IV||1 November 1968 \u2013 22 February 1969||635th Combat Support Group<ref name=635SCOWfacts/>\n|-\n|[[Image:Streamer VS.PNG|200px]]||Tet 1969/Counteroffensive||23 February 1969 \u2013 8 June 1969||635th Combat Support Group<ref name=635SCOWfacts/>\n|-\n|[[Image:Streamer VS.PNG|200px]]||Vietnam Summer-Fall 1969||9 June 1969 \u2013 31 October 1969||635th Combat Support Group<ref name=635SCOWfacts/>\n|-\n|[[Image:Streamer VS.PNG|200px]]||Vietnam Winter-Spring 1970||3 November 1969 \u2013 30 April 1970||635th Combat Support Group<ref name=635SCOWfacts/>\n|-\n|[[Image:Streamer VS.PNG|200px]]||Sanctuary Counteroffensive||1 May 1970 \u2013 30 June 1970||635th Combat Support Group<ref name=635SCOWfacts/>\n|-\n|[[Image:Streamer VS.PNG|200px]]||Southwest Monsoon||1 July 1970 \u2013 30 November 1970||635th Combat Support Group<ref name=635SCOWfacts/>\n|-\n|[[Image:Streamer VS.PNG|200px]]||Commando Hunt V||1 December 1970 \u2013 14 May 1971||635th Combat Support Group<ref name=635SCOWfacts/>\n|-\n|[[Image:Streamer VS.PNG|200px]]||Commando Hunt VI||15 May 1971 \u2013 31 July 1971||635th Combat Support Group<ref name=635SCOWfacts/>\n|-\n|[[Image:Streamer VS.PNG|200px]]||Commando Hunt VII||1 November 1971 \u2013 29 March 1972||635th Combat Support Group<ref name=635SCOWfacts/>\n|-\n|[[Image:Streamer VS.PNG|200px]]||Operation Frequent Wind||29 April 1975 - 30 April 1975||635th Combat Support Group<ref name=635SCOWfacts/>\n|}\n\n==References==\n\n===Notes===\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{Air Force Historical Research Agency}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.Scott.af.mil/ Scott AFB Home Page]\n\n{{USAF Material Command}}\n{{US Air Force navbox}}\n\n[[Category:Military units and formations in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Wings of the United States Air Force|0635]]\n[[Category:Logistics units and formations of the United States Air Force]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 2010]]\n", "name_user": "Lineagegeek", "label": "safe", "comment": "(GR)File renamed:File:635SCOW.jpg\u2192File:635 Supply Chain Operations Wg.jpgReplace unfamiliar abbreviation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/635th_Supply_Chain_Operations_Wing"}
{"title_page": "Lupe Hern\u00e1ndez", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|section=|\n{{More citations needed|date=January 2020}}\n}}\n{{Dubious |reason=There is a chance this person does not exist, all the sources are only referencing each other and there is almost no information about her.|date=April 2020}}\n'''Lupe Hern\u00e1ndez''' is an American nurse who, as a student nurse in 1966, invented the now ubiquitous [[hand sanitizer]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Barton |first1=Laura |title=Hand sanitisers: saved by the gel? |url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2012/may/13/do-we-really-need-hand-sanitisers |website=The Guardian |accessdate=30 March 2020 |date=13 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nHern\u00e1ndez invented the hand sanitizer while a student nurse in [[Bakersfield, California|Bakersfield]], California in 1966, discovering that a substance with 60-65% alcohol could become a cleanser without the need for water and soap.<ref>{{cite web |title=Lupe Hernandez, la mujer que invent\u00f3 el alcohol en gel |url=http://www.rfi.fr/es/salud/20200318-lupe-hernandez-la-mujer-que-invent%C3%B3-el-alcohol-en-gel |website=RFI |accessdate=30 March 2020 |date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nWhile little biographical information is available,<ref>{{cite web |title=Mujeres Bacanas {{!}} Lupe Hern\u00e1ndez |url=http://mujeresbacanas.com/lupe-hernandez/ |website=Mujeres Bacanas |accessdate=30 March 2020 |language=es-CL |date=23 March 2020}}</ref> if alive, she should be in her mid-70s. It has also been reported that Lupe Hernandez is male, although the veracity of this claim cannot be verified. <ref>{{cite web |title=Is Lupe H Hernandez inventor of hand sanitizer still alive? |url = https://www.answers.com/Q/Is_Lupe_H_Hernandez_inventor_of_hand_sanitizer_still_alive |website=Answers.com |accessdate=19 April 2020 | date= 19 October 2012}}</ref>\n\nNevertheless, there is no ascertainable information about even the existence of such Lupe Hern\u00e1ndez and nobody has a record of such a patent file, so it looks like this story is nothing more than an urban legend. It has no documental support even in Bakersfield Museum<ref>{{cite web|url=https://invention.si.edu/lupe-hernandez-and-invention-hand-sanitizer|title=Lupe Hernandez and the Invention of Hand Sanitizer {{!}} Joyce Bedi|date=23 March 2020|website=LEMELSON CENTER for the Study of Invention and Innovation|language=en-US|accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:American inventors]]\n[[Category:American nurses]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|section=|\n{{More citations needed|date=January 2020}}\n}}\n{{Dubious |reason=There is a chance this person does not exist, all the sources are only referencing each other and there is almost no information about her.|date=April 2020}}\n'''Lupe Hern\u00e1ndez''' is an American nurse who, as a student nurse in 1966, invented the now ubiquitous [[hand sanitizer]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Barton |first1=Laura |title=Hand sanitisers: saved by the gel? |url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2012/may/13/do-we-really-need-hand-sanitisers |website=The Guardian |accessdate=30 March 2020 |date=13 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nHern\u00e1ndez invented the hand sanitizer while a student nurse in [[Bakersfield, California|Bakersfield]], California in 1966, discovering that a substance with 60-65% alcohol could become a cleanser without the need for water and soap.<ref>{{cite web |title=Lupe Hernandez, la mujer que invent\u00f3 el alcohol en gel |url=http://www.rfi.fr/es/salud/20200318-lupe-hernandez-la-mujer-que-invent%C3%B3-el-alcohol-en-gel |website=RFI |accessdate=30 March 2020 |date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nWhile little biographical information is available,<ref>{{cite web |title=Mujeres Bacanas {{!}} Lupe Hern\u00e1ndez |url=http://mujeresbacanas.com/lupe-hernandez/ |website=Mujeres Bacanas |accessdate=30 March 2020 |language=es-CL |date=23 March 2020}}</ref> if alive, she should be in her mid-70s. It has also been reported the Lupe Hernandez is male, although the veracity of this claim cannot be verified. <ref>{{cite web |title=Is Lupe H Hernandez inventor of hand sanitizer still alive? |url = https://www.answers.com/Q/Is_Lupe_H_Hernandez_inventor_of_hand_sanitizer_still_alive |website=Answers.com |accessdate=19 April 2020 | date= 19 October 2012}}</ref>\n\nNevertheless, there is no ascertainable information about even the existence of such Lupe Hern\u00e1ndez and nobody has a record of such a patent file, so it looks like this story is nothing more than an urban legend. It has no documental support even in Bakersfield Museum<ref>{{cite web|url=https://invention.si.edu/lupe-hernandez-and-invention-hand-sanitizer|title=Lupe Hernandez and the Invention of Hand Sanitizer {{!}} Joyce Bedi|date=23 March 2020|website=LEMELSON CENTER for the Study of Invention and Innovation|language=en-US|accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:American inventors]]\n[[Category:American nurses]]\n", "name_user": "Chalax91", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixed typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lupe_Hern%C3%A1ndez"}
{"title_page": "Squirm", "text_new": "{{good article}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Squirm\n| image          = Squirmposter.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster \n| producer       = George Manasse\n| director       = [[Jeff Lieberman]]\n| writer         = Jeff Lieberman\n| starring       = {{plainlist |\n* [[Don Scardino]]\n* [[Patricia Pearcy]]\n* R.A. Dow\n* [[Jean Sullivan]]\n* Peter MacLean\n* Fran Higgins\n* [[William Newman (actor)|William Newman]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Robert Prince (composer)|Robert Prince]]\n| cinematography = Joseph Mangine\n| editing        = Brian Smedley-Aston\n| studio = The Squirm Company\n| distributor    = [[American International Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1976|07|14}}\n| country        = United States\n| runtime        = 93 minutes\n| language       = English\n| budget         = \n| gross          = \n}}\n\n'''''Squirm''''' is a 1976 American [[List of natural horror films|natural horror film]] written and directed by [[Jeff Lieberman]]. It stars [[Don Scardino]], [[Patricia Pearcy]], R.A. Dow, [[Jean Sullivan]], Peter MacLean, Fran Higgins, and [[William Newman (actor)|William Newman]]. The film takes place in the fictional town of Fly Creek, [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], which becomes infested with carnivorous worms after a storm directs electricity from power lines onto wet soil. Lieberman was inspired to write the script from a childhood event involving electrocuting the ground and worms coming out.\n\nWith a majority of the budget funded by [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] producers [[Edgar Lansbury (producer)|Edgar Lansbury]] and Joseph Beruh, the film was shot in [[Port Wentworth, Georgia]] in the course of five weeks. Millions of worms from Georgia and [[Maine]] were used during filming. Makeup artist [[Rick Baker (makeup artist)|Rick Baker]] provided special effects for the film, using prosthetic makeup for the first time in his career. Being picked up for distribution by [[American International Pictures]], the film was edited down from an \"R\" rating to a \"PG\" rating. The film received negative reviews from critics but was still financially successful. ''Squirm'' was featured a tenth-season episode of the comedy television series ''[[Mystery Science Theater 3000]]'' in 1999.\n\n==Plot==\nOn the evening of September 29, 1975, in the rural town of Fly Creek, Georgia, wind from a powerful storm knocks an [[overhead power line]] down onto wet soil and starts to electrocute the worms underneath, leaving the town without electricity. The next morning, Geraldine \"Geri\" Sanders' boyfriend Mick is to arrive from New York City for a vacation in Fly Creek; she uses a truck belonging to her neighbor, worm farmer Roger Grimes, to pick up Mick. While the two go to town to get ice for the refrigerator, Roger's shipment of 100,000 [[Glycera (annelid)|bloodworms]] and [[Alitta virens|sandworms]] escape the truck. Mick enters a diner, where a customer says that over 300 thousand volts are being released into the ground from severed power lines. Mick orders an [[egg cream]], and finds a worm in it, though the owner and Sheriff Jim Reston believe he is pulling a prank.\n\nGeri introduces Mick to her mother, Naomi, and sister, Alma, before they both leave to browse at antique dealer Aaron Beardsley's house. Outside, Roger's father Willie finds the entire shipment of worms missing, and berates him for not paying attention to his work. Roger sees Mick alongside Geri and becomes envious of their relationship. Geri and Mick arrive at Beardsley's house; they do not find him, but Geri sees a human skeleton outside the property. They both bring Sheriff Reston over, but the remains disappear. Reston, thinking it is another prank, threatens to arrest Mick if he is seen in town again. When they ask around about Beardsley's whereabouts, they find out he was last seen before the storm. Mick believes that he himself unintentionally released the worms, so he apologizes to Roger and invites him out fishing with him and Geri. They later find the skeleton again, this time in Roger's truck.\n\nWhile on the boat, Mick is bitten when baiting his hook. Roger tells him that worms attack when electrified, and shows them his thumb was bitten by one as a child when Willie experimented with electricity at night. Mick leaves Geri with Roger so he can tend to his wound, and, alongside Alma, takes the skull from the truck to an abandoned dental office. Comparing its teeth with [[Dental radiography|X-rays]], they confirm that it is Beardsley's. Roger makes advances towards Geri against her wishes, but the worms they brought as bait attack him and crawl into his face. He runs off into the woods, and Geri tells Mick. When they try to find him at the worm farm, Mick finds Willie's body being eaten by the worms. They try telling Sheriff Reston again, but he does not listen to them. Mick deduces that Beardsley was killed by the worms, but cannot figure out why.\n\nWhile Mick and Geri are eating dinner with Naomi and Alma, the worms eat through the roots of a tree, causing it to crash into the house. Mick realizes that electricity is still being released from the power lines with the wet soil acting as a conductor, and also remembers that the worms only come out at night. He tells Geri to keep everyone inside equipped with candles and leaves to get plywood to board up the house. He is attacked and knocked unconscious by Roger, whose face is now deformed from the worms. Roger enters the house and kidnaps Geri. The worms infest the house, and numerous places in town are also taken over by them: Sheriff Reston and a woman are eaten alive in a jail cell, and people at Quigley's, a local bar, are also attacked and eaten.\n\nMick regains consciousness and finds Naomi's remains, covered in worms, at the house. When he goes upstairs, Roger attacks and chases him downstairs. Mick pushes Roger into a worm pile, where he is submerged. Mick frees Geri, and tells her that Naomi, and presumably Alma, are dead. The two try to escape, but Roger bites Mick in the leg while they climb out of a window. Mick beats Roger to death, before climbing into a tree, where he and Geri stay until morning. The worms disappear, and they both wake up to a repairman telling them the power has been restored. It is revealed that Alma survived when she climbs out of a [[Chest (furniture)|chest]] she had been hiding in, with Geri and Mick rushing into the house to meet her.\n\n==Cast==\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* [[Don Scardino]] as Mick\t\n* [[Patricia Pearcy]] as Geraldine \"Geri\" Sanders\t\n* R.A. Dow as Roger Grimes\n* [[Jean Sullivan]] as Naomi Sanders\n* Peter MacLean as Sheriff Jim Reston\n* Fran Higgins as Alma Sanders\n* [[William Newman (actor)|William Newman]] as Quigley\n* Barbara Quinn as the sheriff's girl\n* Carl Dagenhart as Willie Grimes\n* Angel Sande as Millie\n* Carol Jean Owens as Lizzie\n* Kim Leon Iocovozzi as Hank\n* Walter Dimmick as Danny\n* Leslie Thorsen as Bonnie\n* Julia Klopp as Mrs. Klopp\n}}\n\n==Production==\n[[File:Rick Baker February 2015 (cropped).jpg|right|thumb|175px|[[Special make-up effects]] artist [[Rick Baker]] provided the make-up for ''Squirm''.]]\n''Squirm'' was written by [[Jeff Lieberman]], who was also working for [[Janus Films]] at the time on a series called ''The Art of Film''. Lieberman said the script was inspired by a true event, where his brother connected an [[electric locomotive|electric train]] [[transformer]] to the ground, causing worms to come out of the ground. He completed the rough draft in six weeks before giving it to producer George Manasse, who saw potential in it. Manasse showed it to then-independent [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] producers [[Edgar Lansbury (producer)|Edgar Lansbury]] and Joseph Beruh, who bought ''Squirm'' in 1975. Though they had only a few investors, both of them still invested $470,000 into the project. The original filming location and setting was planned for [[New England]]<ref name=\"Fangoria1993\">{{cite magazine|magazine=[[Fangoria]]|title=The Squirm Turns|last=Szulkin|first=David|pages=24\u201329|date=June 1993|issue=123|url=https://archive.org/details/Fangoria_123_1993_Ticks_DaveWooderson-DREGS_c2c/page/n23}}</ref> but instead changed to [[Port Wentworth, Georgia]]{{sfn|Muir|2012|p=18}} due to the former's weather conditions during [[autumn]].<ref name=\"Fangoria1993\" /> \n\nProduction first began in November 1975. Half of the worms used in the film were fake and made of rubber, the other half included large [[Arenicola marina|sandworms]] from Maine that were taken from the ground by using a wire connected to a [[Potentiometer#Rheostat|rheostat]]. They were then refrigerated and transported to Port Wentworth.<ref name=\"Fangoria1993\"/> The [[Skidaway Institute of Oceanography|University of Georgia Oceanographic Insitute]] from [[Skidaway Island, Georgia]] also provided an estimated three million [[Glycera (annelid)|''Glycera'']] worms for use.<ref name=AFI>{{cite web|url=https://catalog.afi.com/Catalog/moviedetails/55262|title=Squirm|work=[[AFI Catalog of Feature Films]]|accessdate=March 17, 2020}}</ref> One scene involving a living room filled with worms was accomplished by building a [[scaffolding]] four feet above the ground with a canvas placed on top, and covering the canvas with thousands of worms until it was six inches deep. The local [[Boy Scouts of America|Boy Scouts]] troop were hired to assist in handling the worms. They received [[Merit badge (Boy Scouts of America)|merit badges]] for their work.<ref name=BoxOffice1>{{cite magazine|magazine=[[Box Office (magazine)|Box Office]]|title=Horror-Thriller 'Squirm' Completed in Georgia|author=Staff Writer|date=January 12, 1976|page=16}}</ref> After production wrapped, newspapers in [[Maine]] reported that the film production ruined the fishing industry due to the lack of worms for use.<ref name=\"Fangoria1993\"/>\n\nBrian Smedley-Aston, who had previous film credits including [[Performance (film)|''Performance'']], [[Tom Jones (1963 film)|''Tom Jones'']], and ''[[The Shuttered Room]]'', did the [[film editing]].<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=[[Shivers (magazine)|Shivers]]|title=Expose|last=Lynn|first=France|issue=3|pages=19\u201321|date=October 1992|url=https://archive.org/details/Shivers_03/page/n17}}</ref> [[Robert Prince (composer)|Robert Prince]] was the composer for the movie, conducting a full-orchestra soundtrack in [[England]]. [[Bernard Hermann]], composer for ''[[The Day the Earth Stood Still]]'' and [[Psycho (1960 film)|''Psycho'']], was originally slated to write the score but died before beginning work.<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=[[Starlog]]|title=Squirm|last=O'Quinn|first=Kerry|issue=1|date=August 1976|pages=20\u201321}}</ref> Joe Mangine was the [[director of photography]] while Henry Shrady was the [[art director]].<ref name=BoxOffice1/> [[Special make-up effects]] artist [[Rick Baker]] created the make-up in New York for Richard A. Dow's character Roger when he turns into \"Wormface\", and made a facial mold using [[Prosthetic makeup|prosthetics]], which were then new to him.<ref name=\"Fangoria1993\"/>\n\n[[Principal photography]] wrapped after five weeks, with seven days dedicated to working with the worms. Lieberman was heavily involved with the [[post-production]], including making the sound effects for the worms. This was done by using [[balloons]] and shears and looping the two sounds through [[multitrack recording]]. The worms also screamed; this sound was taken from [[Brian De Palma]]'s 1976 film [[Carrie (1976 film)|''Carrie'']], specifically the scene in which pigs are slaughtered.<ref name=\"Fangoria1993\"/>\n\n==Release==\n''Squirm'' was shown at the [[1976 Cannes Film Festival]]. It was later acquired by [[American International Pictures]] (AIP), who released it theatrically in the [[United States]] on July 14, 1976 and worldwide on August 9th.<ref name=AFI/><ref name=BoxOffice2>{{cite magazine|magazine=[[Box Office (magazine)|Box Office]]|title=AIP Arranges July Release of Terror Drama 'Squirm'|author=Staff Writer|date=July 19, 1976|page=5}}</ref> AIP had given a $250,000 advancement to the film producers for domestic distribution and $500,000 in guarantees from sixteen territories.<ref name=AFI/> When the movie was first submitted to the [[Motion Picture Association of America]] (MPAA), AIP intended the film to get a \"PG\" rating. The MPAA instead gave the film an \"R\" rating, citing certain scenes in the film that were \"objectionable to PG-rated sensibilities\".<ref name=\"Fangoria1993\"/> AIP would later make edits to the film in an attempt to get it to \"PG\". The re-edit would later be shown as the television version. Despite the edits, however, the movie was still financially successful, with producers Edgar Lansbury and Joseph Beruh making their investment back from the foreign theatrical market.<ref name=\"Fangoria1993\"/>\n\nThe film was released on [[VHS]] by [[Vestron Video]] in 1983.<ref name=\"Fangoria1983\">{{cite magazine|magazine=[[Fangoria]]|title=The Video Eye of Dr. Cyclops|author=Dr. Cyclops|issue=29|date=September 1983|page=27|url=https://archive.org/details/Fangoria_029_c2c_1983_Gates_of_Hell_Sproutcore-Bollywox-DREGS/page/n29}}</ref> It was later released on [[DVD]] by [[MGM Home Entertainment]] in 2003. The DVD restored a shower scene with Patricia Pearcy, and [[audio commentary]] with Jeff Lieberman was included in the special features.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dvdtalk.com/reviews/7452/squirm-se/|title=Squirm: SE|last=Gross|first=G. Noel|work=DVD Talk|date=August 26, 2003|accessdate=December 5, 2019}}</ref> MGM later released in 2011 as part of a set with [[Swamp Thing (film)|''Swamp Thing'']] and ''[[The Return of the Living Dead]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmovie.com/movie/squirm-v46341/releases|title=Squirm - Releases|publisher=[[Allmovie]]|accessdate=December 3, 2019}}</ref> The unedited R-rated version was released in the United Kingdom on [[Blu-ray]] and DVD by [[Arrow Video]] on September 23, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.blu-ray.com/movies/Squirm-Blu-ray/66040/|title=Squirm Blu-ray|publisher=Bly-ray.com|date=September 23, 2013|accessdate=December 5, 2013}}</ref> This same version was released in the United States on Blu-ray by [[Shout! Factory]] under its Scream Factory label on October 28, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/home-video/3310212/scream-factory-will-make-squirm-halloween/|title=Scream Factory! Will Make You \u2018Squirm\u2019 This Halloween|last=Miska|first=Brad|work=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|date=August 26, 2014|accessdate=August 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Reception===\nOn [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film has an approval rating of 36% based on 14 reviews with an average rating of 4.6 out of 10.<ref name=\"rtomatoesrating\">{{cite web|title=Squirm (1976) - Rotten Tomatoes|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/squirm/|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=December 5, 2016}}</ref> [[Vincent Canby]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' wrote that Scardino and Pearcy gave decent performances, and scenes with the worms were \"effectively revolting\", but criticized the special effects, comparing the shot of Roger sinking into a worm pile with \"spaghetti with meat sauce\".<ref>{{cite journal |last=Canby |first=Vincent |authorlink=Vincent Canby |date=July 31, 1976 |title=The Screen:'Squirm' Shows Worms Turning on People |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1976/07/31/archives/the-screensquirm-shows-worms-turning-on-people.html |journal=[[The New York Times]] |page=8 }}</ref> ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' declared that the actual \"creepy\" special effects were thrown off by \"clumsy and amateurish\" effects, though there was \"admirable earnestness\" for the effort.<ref>{{cite journal |date=August 11, 1976 |title=Squirm |url= |journal=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |page=19 }}</ref> [[Kevin Thomas (film critic)|Kevin Thomas]] of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' called it \"a nifty little horror film that strikes a good balance between humor and terror\", and praised Lieberman for displaying \"plenty of panache\", and \"deftly playing a disarming folksy atmosphere against rapidly escalating peril\".<ref>[[Kevin Thomas (film critic)|Thomas, Kevin]] (December 17, 1976). \"As the Worm Turns: 'Squirm'\". ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''. Part IV, p. 21.</ref> John Pym of ''[[The Monthly Film Bulletin]]'' wrote that Lieberman's \"restrained use of the worms, [...] flourishes of black humour and, above all, his determination to trim the narrative and not to strive for overblown or fantastic effects\" made ''Squirm'' commendable and a scary addition \"to a recently thriving genre\".<ref>{{cite journal |last=Pym |first=John |date=September 1976 |title=Squirm |url= |journal=[[The Monthly Film Bulletin]] |volume=43 |issue=512 |page=199 }}</ref> ''[[Cinefantastique]]'' contributor Kyle B. Counts criticized Lieberman's direction for cutting away from violent moments in the film to scenes of [[comic relief]].<ref name=Cinefantastique>{{cite magazine|magazine=[[Cinefantastique]]|title=Film Ratings|last=Counts|first=Kyle|volume=5|number=3|date=Winter 1976|page=29|url=https://archive.org/details/Cinefantastique0503Starbrite/page/n27}}</ref> [[John Kenneth Muir]] rated the film a mixed two and a half out of four stars, calling it \"a letdown\". While he commended the cinematography and imagery, Muir stated that the film's inconsistent tone and lack of believable characters undermined the whole experience.{{sfn|Muir|2012|pp=134-136}}\n\nDonald Guarisco for [[AllMovie]] gave the film three and a half out of five stars, praising the acting and musical score. Guarisco added that ''Squirm'' was an \"excellent example of the 'revenge of nature' horror\" genre.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmovie.com/movie/squirm-v46341/review|title=Squirm (1976)|last=Guarisco|first=Donald|work=[[Allmovie]]|accessdate=August 7, 2019}}</ref> Film critic [[Leonard Maltin]] gave it three out of four stars, calling it an \"above-average horror outing [that] builds to good shock sequences\".{{sfn|Maltin|2013|p=1318}} [[TV Guide]], while giving it two out of four stars, said it was \"an underrated effort\" like Lieberman's other works.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tvguide.com/movies/squirm/review/118818/|title=Squirm Review|work=[[TV Guide]]|accessdate=August 7, 2019}}</ref> Jim Craddock, author of ''VideoHound's Golden Movie Retriever'', also gave two stars, calling it an \"okay\" giant worm movie.{{sfn|Craddock|2006|p=809}} In his book ''American International Pictures: A Comprehensive Filmography'', Rob Craig considered it to be \"an entertaining - and fairly insightful \u2212 film which is certainly not uncritical to its main characters and their community\". Craig also gave praise to Rick Baker's make-up effects.{{sfn|Craig|2019|page=349}} Kate Abbott for [[Time (magazine)|''Time'']] called it one of the best \"Killer-Animal Movies\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://entertainment.time.com/2010/08/20/top-10-killer-animal-movies/slide/squirm/|title=Top 10 Killer-Animal Movies|last=Abbott|first=Kate|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|page=6|date=August 19, 2010|accessdate=December 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Analysis==\n''Squirm'' can be seen as part of a tradition of 1970s \"revenge of nature\" films, the most important of which was ''[[Jaws (film)|Jaws]]''.{{sfn|Verevis|2016|p=102}}{{sfn|Platts|2015|pp=156-7}} This began in the early 1970s with films like ''[[Frogs (film)|Frogs]]'', ''[[Night of the Lepus]]'', and ''[[Sssssss]]'', leading on to ''Jaws'', ''Squirm'', ''[[Empire of the Ants (film)|Empire of the Ants]]'' and ''[[Kingdom of the Spiders]]''.{{sfn|Verevis|2016|p=102}} It can even be seen, along with other \"nature-running-amok thrillers\" of the latter half of the 1970s (like ''[[The Food of the Gods (film)|The Food of the Gods]]'', ''[[The Pack (1977 film)|The Pack]]'', ''[[The Car]]'', ''[[The Swarm (film)|The Swarm]]'', ''Empire of the Ants'', ''[[Long Weekend (1978 film)|Long Weekend]]'', and ''[[Day of the Animals]]''), as a \"''Jaws''ploitation\" film, a film [[exploitation film|exploiting]] the success of ''Jaws''.{{sfn|Hunter|2016|p=85}} The [[film studies]] scholar I. Q. Hunter disputes this, however, arguing that ''Jaws'' merely served to perpetuate the early-1970s genre that [[Quentin Tarantino]] called the \"Mother Nature goes ape-shit kind of movie\".{{sfn|Hunter|2016|p=85}} Muir calls ''Squirm'' one of the \"eco-horrors\" of the 1970s, along with ''Frogs'', ''Night of the Lepus'', ''Day of the Animals'', ''Kingdom of the Spiders'', ''Empire of the Ants'', ''The Swarm'', and ''[[Prophecy (film)|Prophecy]]''. These films reflected attitudes and fears prevalent at the time; specifically, they reflected the public's unease about what he called \"man's continued pillaging and pollution of the Earth\".{{sfn|Muir|2012|p=2}}\n\n[[Robin Wood (critic)|Robin Wood]] used ''Squirm'' as an example of nature films linking \"natural\" force to sexual and familiar tensions. Wood also expressed disappointment with the film's ending, as he felt the survival of Mick, Geri, and Alma counteracted the film's logic. He interpreted the film's world being \"totally overwhelmed by eruptions of devouring worms that develop, initially, out of familiar constraints and sexual possessiveness\".{{sfn|Wood|2018}} Kyle B. Counts notes similarities between ''Squirm'' and [[Straw Dogs (1971 film)|''Straw Dogs'']] in their themes of \"masculine ideals\". In both, the male leads play the hero. The reviewer, however, believed that the film did not give the impression that Don Scardino's character grew into a \"man\" after his experience.<ref name=Cinefantastique/>\n\nIn 2014, Liberman wrote a [[foreword]] for the book ''Subversive Horror Cinema: Countercultural Messages of Films from Frankenstein to the Present'' by Jon Towlson. In this, he addressed the critical and scholarly analysis of ''Squirm'':\n\n{{Cquote|quote=In my first movie, ''Squirm'' (1976), I really didn't try to make any sort of social or political comment. At least not consciously. However, soon after the movie's release, critics found some very profound subtexts which I myself wasn't aware of. Nature getting revenge on man for his disrespect of ecology. The symbolism of man's mortality and his inevitable fate of becoming worm food. Even themes of suppressed sexuality in the main characters. This could all very well be true, but if it is, it was not done purposely on my part.|author=[[Jeff Lieberman]]|source=''Subversive Horror Cinema: Countercultural Messages of Films from Frankenstein to the Present'' {{sfn|Towlson|2014|p=1}}}}\n\n==Legacy==\nDirector Brian De Palma included a poster of ''Squirm'' in several scenes of his 1981 film ''[[Blow Out]]''. Jeff Lieberman, who idolized De Palma, said in a ''[[Fangoria]]'' interview that he met the director years later and asked him about the poster. De Palma reportedly answered \"Only use the best!\"<ref name=\"Fangoria1993\"/> Pittsburgh musician [[Weird Paul Petroskey]] created an entire album, ''Worm in My Egg Cream'', dedicated to the \"worm in the egg cream\" scene and making extensive use of samples from the film. All 16 tracks on the album are titled \"Worm in My Egg Cream\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.weirdpaul.com/discography.html|title=THE MUSIC OF WEIRD PAUL|website=www.weirdpaul.com|access-date=April 11, 2017}}</ref>\n\n''Squirm'' was featured in a tenth-season episode of ''[[Mystery Science Theater 3000]]'' (''MST3K''), a comedy television series whose premise is that the character [[Mike Nelson (character)|Mike Nelson]] and his two robot friends [[Crow T. Robot]] and [[Tom Servo]] are forced to watch bad films as part of an ongoing scientific experiment. Broadcast on the [[Sci-Fi Channel]] on August 1, 1999, it was the penultimate episode to the series, ending with ''[[Danger: Diabolik]]'' a week later.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tvguide.com/tvshows/mystery-science-theater-3000/episodes/203329/|title=Mystery Science Theater 3000 Season 10 Episode Guide|work=[[TV Guide]]|accessdate=August 2, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"DVD\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dvdtalk.com/reviews/65514/mystery-science-theater-3000-the-turkey-day-collection-xxxi/|title=Mystery Science Theater 3000: The Turkey Day Collection|last=Sinnott|first=John|work=DVD Talk|date=November 25, 2014|accessdate=August 2, 2019}}</ref> It was shown along with the short film ''[[A Case of Spring Fever]]''.<ref name=\"DVD\"/> In response to the episode, Jeff Lieberman voiced his frustration towards the movie being sold to ''MST3K'', saying it cheapened the value of the movie.<ref name=\"BMD\">{{cite web|url=https://birthmoviesdeath.com/2013/08/14/why-the-director-of-squirm-was-furious-about-the-mst3k-version-of-his-movie|title=Why The Director Of SQUIRM Was Furious About The MST3K Version Of His Movie|last=Faraci|first=Devin|work=Birth.Movies.Death.|date=August 14, 2013|accessdate=August 4, 2019}}</ref> In 2014, Shout! Factory released the ''MST3K'' episode as part of the \"Turkey Day Collection\", along with episodes focused on ''[[Jungle Goddess]]'', ''[[The Painted Hills]]'', and ''[[The Screaming Skull]]''.<ref name=\"DVD\"/>\n\n==References==\n===Citations===\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Craddock|first=Jim|title=VideoHound's Golden Movie Retriever|date=2006|publisher=Gale Group|url-access=registration|isbn=0-7876-8980-7|url=https://archive.org/details/videohoundsgolde2006crad}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Craig|first=Rob|title=American International Pictures: A Comprehensive Filmography|date=2019|publisher=[[McFarland & Company]]|isbn=978-1-4766-6631-0|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=e0CIDwAAQBAJ}}\n*{{cite book|ref={{sfnref|Hunter|2016|p=85}}|author=I.Q. Hunter|title=Cult Film as a Guide to Life: Fandom, Adaptation, and Identity|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KaqaDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA85|date=8 September 2016|publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing|isbn=978-1-62356-381-3}}\n*{{cite book|ref={{sfnref|Maltin|2013|p=1318}}|last1=Maltin|first1=Leonard|last2=Carson|first2=Darwyn|title=Leonard Maltin's Movie Guide: The Modern Era|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780451418104|url-access=registration|year=2013|publisher=Signet|isbn=978-0-451-41810-4}}\n*{{cite book|ref={{sfnref|Muir|2012|pp=134-136}}|last=Muir|first=John|title=Horror Films of the 1970s|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ghmYvJReqIIC|date=November 22, 2012|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-0-7864-9156-8}}\n*{{cite book|last=Platts|first=Todd K.|year=2015|chapter=The New Horror Movie|editor1-last=Cogan|editor1-first=Brian|editor2-last=Gencarelli|editor2-first=Thom|title=Baby Boomers and Popular Culture|publisher=Praeger|ref=harv|pages=147-64}}\n*{{cite book|last=Towlson|first=Jon|title=Subversive Horror Cinema: Countercultural Messages of Films from Frankenstein to the Present|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RIgOAwAAQBAJ|date=2014|publisher=McFarland|isbn=147-6-6153-30}}\n*{{cite book|ref={{sfnref|Verevis|2016|p=102}}|last=Verevis|first=Constantine|chapter=Vicious cycle: ''Jaws'' and the revenge-of-nature films of the 1970s|editor1=Amanda Ann Klein|editor2=R. Barton Palmer|title=Cycles, Sequels, Spin-offs, Remakes, and Reboots: Multiplicities in Film and Television|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IvK4CwAAQBAJ&pg=PA102|date=March 15, 2016|publisher=University of Texas Press|isbn=978-1-4773-0817-2}}\n*{{cite book|last=Wood|first=Robin|year=2018|title=Robin Wood on the Horror Film: Collected Essays and Reviews|chapter=Return of the Repressed|publisher=[[Wayne State University Press]]|isbn=0-8143-4524-7|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lfRLDwAAQBAJ}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Amg title|46341|Squirm}}\n* {{AFI film|55262|Squirm}}\n* {{IMDb title|0075261|Squirm}}\n* {{tcmdb title|20595|Squirm}}\n\n{{Jeff Lieberman}}\n\n[[Category:1976 films]]\n[[Category:1976 horror films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American International Pictures films]]\n[[Category:American natural horror films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Jeff Lieberman]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Robert Prince]]\n[[Category:Films set in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Films featured on Mystery Science Theater 3000]]\n", "text_old": "{{good article}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Squirm\n| image          = Squirmposter.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster \n| producer       = George Manasse\n| director       = [[Jeff Lieberman]]\n| writer         = Jeff Lieberman\n| starring       = {{plainlist |\n* [[Don Scardino]]\n* [[Patricia Pearcy]]\n* R.A. Dow\n* [[Jean Sullivan]]\n* Peter MacLean\n* Fran Higgins\n* [[William Newman (actor)|William Newman]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Robert Prince (composer)|Robert Prince]]\n| cinematography = Joseph Mangine\n| editing        = Brian Smedley-Aston\n| studio = The Squirm Company\n| distributor    = [[American International Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1976|07|14}}\n| country        = United States\n| runtime        = 93 minutes\n| language       = English\n| budget         = \n| gross          = \n}}\n\n'''''Squirm''''' is a 1976 American [[List of natural horror films|natural horror film]] written and directed by [[Jeff Lieberman]]. It stars [[Don Scardino]], [[Patricia Pearcy]], R.A. Dow, [[Jean Sullivan]], Peter MacLean, Fran Higgins, and [[William Newman (actor)|William Newman]]. The film takes place in the fictional town of Fly Creek, [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], which becomes infested with carnivorous worms after a storm directs electricity from power lines onto wet soil. Lieberman was inspired to write the script from a childhood event involving electrocuting the ground and worms coming out.\n\nWith a majority of the budget funded by [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] producers [[Edgar Lansbury (producer)|Edgar Lansbury]] and Joseph Beruh, the film was shot in [[Port Wentworth, Georgia]] in the course of five weeks. Millions of worms from Georgia and [[Maine]] were used during filming. Makeup artist [[Rick Baker (makeup artist)|Rick Baker]] provided special effects for the film, using prosthetic makeup for the first time in his career. Being picked up for distribution by [[American International Pictures]], the film was edited down from an \"R\" rating to a \"PG\" rating. The film received negative reviews from critics but was still financially successful. ''Squirm'' was featured a tenth-season episode of the comedy television series ''[[Mystery Science Theater 3000]]'' in 1999.\n\n==Plot==\nOn the evening of September 29, 1975, in the rural town of Fly Creek, Georgia, wind from a powerful storm knocks an [[overhead power line]] down onto wet soil and starts to electrocute the worms underneath, leaving the town without electricity. The next morning, Geraldine \"Geri\" Sanders' boyfriend Mick is to arrive from New York City for a vacation in Fly Creek; she uses a truck belonging to her neighbor, worm farmer Roger Grimes, to pick up Mick. While the two go to town to get ice for the refrigerator, Roger's shipment of 100,000 [[Glycera (annelid)|bloodworms]] and [[Alitta virens|sandworms]] escape the truck. Mick enters a diner, where a customer says that over 300 thousand volts are being released into the ground from severed power lines. Mick orders an [[egg cream]], and finds a worm in it, though the owner and Sheriff Jim Reston believe he is pulling a prank.\n\nGeri introduces Mick to her mother, Naomi, and sister, Alma, before they both leave to browse at antique dealer Aaron Beardsley's house. Outside, Roger's father Willie finds the entire shipment of worms missing, and berates him for not paying attention to his work. Roger sees Mick alongside Geri and becomes envious of their relationship. Geri and Mick arrive at Beardsley's house; they do not find him, but Geri sees a human skeleton outside the property. They both bring Sheriff Reston over, but the remains disappear. Reston, thinking it is another prank, threatens to arrest Mick if he is seen in town again. When they ask around about Beardsley's whereabouts, they find out he was last seen before the storm. Mick believes that he himself unintentionally released the worms, so he apologizes to Roger and invites him out fishing with him and Geri. They later find the skeleton again, this time in Roger's truck.\n\nWhile on the boat, Mick is bitten when baiting his hook. Roger tells him that worms attack when electrified, and shows them his thumb was bitten by one as a child when Willie experimented with electricity at night. Mick leaves Geri with Roger so he can tend to his wound, and, alongside Alma, takes the skull from the truck to an abandoned dental office. Comparing its teeth with [[Dental radiography|X-rays]], they confirm that it is Beardsley's. Roger makes advances towards Geri against her wishes, but the worms they brought as bait attack him and crawl into his face. He runs off into the woods, and Geri tells Mick. When they try to find him at the worm farm, Mick finds Willie's body being eaten by the worms. They try telling Sheriff Reston again, but he does not listen to them. Mick deduces that Beardsley was killed by the worms, but cannot figure out why.\n\nWhile Mick and Geri are eating dinner with Naomi and Alma, the worms eat through the roots of a tree, causing it to crash into the house. Mick realizes that electricity is still being released from the power lines with the wet soil acting as a conductor, and also remembers that the worms only come out at night. He tells Geri to keep everyone inside equipped with candles and leaves to get plywood to board up the house. He is attacked and knocked unconscious by Roger, whose face is now deformed from the worms. Roger enters the house and kidnaps Geri. The worms infest the house, and numerous places in town are also taken over by them: Sheriff Reston and a woman are eaten alive in a jail cell, and people at Quigley's, a local bar, are also attacked and eaten.\n\nMick regains consciousness and finds Naomi's remains, covered in worms, at the house. When he goes upstairs, Roger attacks and chases him downstairs. Mick pushes Roger into a worm pile, where he is submerged. Mick frees Geri, and tells her that Naomi, and presumably Alma, are dead. The two try to escape, but Roger bites Mick in the leg while they climb out of a window. Mick beats Roger to death, before climbing into a tree, where he and Geri stay until morning. The worms disappear, and they both wake up to a repairman telling them the power has been restored. It is revealed that Alma survived when she climbs out of a [[Chest (furniture)|chest]] she had been hiding in, with Geri and Mick rushing into the house to meet her.\n\n==Cast==\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* [[Don Scardino]] as Mick\t\n* [[Patricia Pearcy]] as Geraldine \"Geri\" Sanders\t\n* R.A. Dow as Roger Grimes\n* [[Jean Sullivan]] as Naomi Sanders\n* Peter MacLean as Sheriff Jim Reston\n* Fran Higgins as Alma Sanders\n* [[William Newman (actor)|William Newman]] as Quigley\n* Barbara Quinn as the sheriff's girl\n* Carl Dagenhart as Willie Grimes\n* Angel Sande as Millie\n* Carol Jean Owens as Lizzie\n* Kim Leon Iocovozzi as Hank\n* Walter Dimmick as Danny\n* Leslie Thorsen as Bonnie\n* Julia Klopp as Mrs. Klopp\n}}\n\n==Production==\n[[File:Rick Baker February 2015 (cropped).jpg|right|thumb|175px|[[Special make-up effects]] artist [[Rick Baker]] provided the make-up for ''Squirm''.]]\n''Squirm'' was written by [[Jeff Lieberman]], who was also working for [[Janus Films]] at the time on a series called ''The Art of Film''. Lieberman said the script was inspired by a true event, where his brother connected an [[electric locomotive|electric train]] [[transformer]] to the ground, causing worms to come out of the ground. He completed the rough draft in six weeks before giving it to producer George Manasse, who saw potential in it. Manasse showed it to then-independent [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] producers [[Edgar Lansbury (producer)|Edgar Lansbury]] and Joseph Beruh, who bought ''Squirm'' in 1975. Though they had only a few investors, both of them still invested $470,000 into the project. The original filming location and setting was planned for [[New England]]<ref name=\"Fangoria1993\">{{cite magazine|magazine=[[Fangoria]]|title=The Squirm Turns|last=Szulkin|first=David|pages=24\u201329|date=June 1993|issue=123|url=https://archive.org/details/Fangoria_123_1993_Ticks_DaveWooderson-DREGS_c2c/page/n23}}</ref> but instead changed to [[Port Wentworth, Georgia]]{{sfn|Muir|2012|p=18}} due to the former's weather conditions during [[autumn]].<ref name=\"Fangoria1993\" /> \n\nProduction first began in November 1975. Half of the worms used in the film were fake and made of rubber, the other half included large [[Arenicola marina|sandworms]] from Maine that were taken from the ground by using a wire connected to a [[Potentiometer#Rheostat|rheostat]]. They were then refrigerated and transported to Port Wentworth.<ref name=\"Fangoria1993\"/> The [[Skidaway Institute of Oceanography|University of Georgia Oceanographic Insitute]] from [[Skidaway Island, Georgia]] also provided an estimated three million [[Glycera (annelid)|''Glycera'']] worms for use.<ref name=AFI>{{cite web|url=https://catalog.afi.com/Catalog/moviedetails/55262|title=Squirm|work=[[AFI Catalog of Feature Films]]|accessdate=March 17, 2020}}</ref> One scene involving a living room filled with worms was accomplished by building a [[scaffolding]] four feet above the ground with a canvas placed on top, and covering the canvas with thousands of worms until it was six inches deep. The local [[Boy Scouts of America|Boy Scouts]] troop were hired to assist in handling the worms. They received [[Merit badge (Boy Scouts of America)|merit badges]] for their work.<ref name=BoxOffice1>{{cite magazine|magazine=[[Box Office (magazine)|Box Office]]|title=Horror-Thriller 'Squirm' Completed in Georgia|author=Staff Writer|date=January 12, 1976|page=16}}</ref> After production wrapped, newspapers in [[Maine]] reported that the film production ruined the fishing industry due to the lack of worms for use.<ref name=\"Fangoria1993\"/>\n\nBrian Smedley-Aston, who had previous film credits including [[Performance (film)|''Performance'']], [[Tom Jones (1963 film)|''Tom Jones'']], and ''[[The Shuttered Room]]'', did the [[film editing]].<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=[[Shivers (magazine)|Shivers]]|title=Expose|last=Lynn|first=France|issue=3|pages=19\u201321|date=October 1992|url=https://archive.org/details/Shivers_03/page/n17}}</ref> [[Robert Prince (composer)|Robert Prince]] was the composer for the movie, conducting a full-orchestra soundtrack in [[England]]. [[Bernard Hermann]], composer for ''[[The Day the Earth Stood Still]]'' and [[Psycho (1960 film)|''Psycho'']], was originally slated to write the score but died before beginning work.<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=[[Starlog]]|title=Squirm|last=O'Quinn|first=Kerry|issue=1|date=August 1976|pages=20\u201321}}</ref> Joe Mangine was the [[director of photography]] while Henry Shrady was the [[art director]].<ref name=BoxOffice1/> [[Special make-up effects]] artist [[Rick Baker]] created the make-up in New York for Richard A. Dow's character Roger when he turns into \"Wormface\", and made a facial mold using [[Prosthetic makeup|prosthetics]], which were then new to him.<ref name=\"Fangoria1993\"/>\n\n[[Principal photography]] wrapped after five weeks, with seven days dedicated to working with the worms. Lieberman was heavily involved with the [[post-production]], including making the sound effects for the worms. This was done by using [[balloons]] and shears and looping the two sounds through [[multitrack recording]]. The worms also screamed; this sound was taken from [[Brian De Palma]]'s 1976 film [[Carrie (1976 film)|''Carrie'']], specifically the scene in which pigs are slaughtered.<ref name=\"Fangoria1993\"/>\n\n==Release==\n''Squirm'' was shown at the [[1976 Cannes Film Festival]]. It was later acquired by [[American International Pictures]] (AIP), who released it theatrically in the [[United States]] on July 14, 1976 and worldwide on August 9th.<ref name=AFI/><ref name=BoxOffice2>{{cite magazine|magazine=[[Box Office (magazine)|Box Office]]|title=AIP Arranges July Release of Terror Drama 'Squirm'|author=Staff Writer|date=July 19, 1976|page=5}}</ref> API had given a $250,000 advancement to the film producers for domestic distribution and $500,000 in guarantees from sixteen territories.<ref name=AFI/> When the movie was first submitted to the [[Motion Picture Association of America]] (MPAA), AIP intended the film to get a \"PG\" rating. The MPAA instead gave the film an \"R\" rating, citing certain scenes in the film that were \"objectionable to PG-rated sensibilities\".<ref name=\"Fangoria1993\"/> AIP would later make edits to the film in an attempt to get it to \"PG\". The re-edit would later be shown as the television version. Despite the edits, however, the movie was still financially successful, with producers Edgar Lansbury and Joseph Beruh making their investment back from the foreign theatrical market.<ref name=\"Fangoria1993\"/>\n\nThe film was released on [[VHS]] by [[Vestron Video]] in 1983.<ref name=\"Fangoria1983\">{{cite magazine|magazine=[[Fangoria]]|title=The Video Eye of Dr. Cyclops|author=Dr. Cyclops|issue=29|date=September 1983|page=27|url=https://archive.org/details/Fangoria_029_c2c_1983_Gates_of_Hell_Sproutcore-Bollywox-DREGS/page/n29}}</ref> It was later released on [[DVD]] by [[MGM Home Entertainment]] in 2003. The DVD restored a shower scene with Patricia Pearcy, and [[audio commentary]] with Jeff Lieberman was included in the special features.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dvdtalk.com/reviews/7452/squirm-se/|title=Squirm: SE|last=Gross|first=G. Noel|work=DVD Talk|date=August 26, 2003|accessdate=December 5, 2019}}</ref> MGM later released in 2011 as part of a set with [[Swamp Thing (film)|''Swamp Thing'']] and ''[[The Return of the Living Dead]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmovie.com/movie/squirm-v46341/releases|title=Squirm - Releases|publisher=[[Allmovie]]|accessdate=December 3, 2019}}</ref> The unedited R-rated version was released in the United Kingdom on [[Blu-ray]] and DVD by [[Arrow Video]] on September 23, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.blu-ray.com/movies/Squirm-Blu-ray/66040/|title=Squirm Blu-ray|publisher=Bly-ray.com|date=September 23, 2013|accessdate=December 5, 2013}}</ref> This same version was released in the United States on Blu-ray by [[Shout! Factory]] under its Scream Factory label on October 28, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/home-video/3310212/scream-factory-will-make-squirm-halloween/|title=Scream Factory! Will Make You \u2018Squirm\u2019 This Halloween|last=Miska|first=Brad|work=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|date=August 26, 2014|accessdate=August 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Reception===\nOn [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film has an approval rating of 36% based on 14 reviews with an average rating of 4.6 out of 10.<ref name=\"rtomatoesrating\">{{cite web|title=Squirm (1976) - Rotten Tomatoes|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/squirm/|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=December 5, 2016}}</ref> [[Vincent Canby]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' wrote that Scardino and Pearcy gave decent performances, and scenes with the worms were \"effectively revolting\", but criticized the special effects, comparing the shot of Roger sinking into a worm pile with \"spaghetti with meat sauce\".<ref>{{cite journal |last=Canby |first=Vincent |authorlink=Vincent Canby |date=July 31, 1976 |title=The Screen:'Squirm' Shows Worms Turning on People |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1976/07/31/archives/the-screensquirm-shows-worms-turning-on-people.html |journal=[[The New York Times]] |page=8 }}</ref> ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' declared that the actual \"creepy\" special effects were thrown off by \"clumsy and amateurish\" effects, though there was \"admirable earnestness\" for the effort.<ref>{{cite journal |date=August 11, 1976 |title=Squirm |url= |journal=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |page=19 }}</ref> [[Kevin Thomas (film critic)|Kevin Thomas]] of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' called it \"a nifty little horror film that strikes a good balance between humor and terror\", and praised Lieberman for displaying \"plenty of panache\", and \"deftly playing a disarming folksy atmosphere against rapidly escalating peril\".<ref>[[Kevin Thomas (film critic)|Thomas, Kevin]] (December 17, 1976). \"As the Worm Turns: 'Squirm'\". ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''. Part IV, p. 21.</ref> John Pym of ''[[The Monthly Film Bulletin]]'' wrote that Lieberman's \"restrained use of the worms, [...] flourishes of black humour and, above all, his determination to trim the narrative and not to strive for overblown or fantastic effects\" made ''Squirm'' commendable and a scary addition \"to a recently thriving genre\".<ref>{{cite journal |last=Pym |first=John |date=September 1976 |title=Squirm |url= |journal=[[The Monthly Film Bulletin]] |volume=43 |issue=512 |page=199 }}</ref> ''[[Cinefantastique]]'' contributor Kyle B. Counts criticized Lieberman's direction for cutting away from violent moments in the film to scenes of [[comic relief]].<ref name=Cinefantastique>{{cite magazine|magazine=[[Cinefantastique]]|title=Film Ratings|last=Counts|first=Kyle|volume=5|number=3|date=Winter 1976|page=29|url=https://archive.org/details/Cinefantastique0503Starbrite/page/n27}}</ref> [[John Kenneth Muir]] rated the film a mixed two and a half out of four stars, calling it \"a letdown\". While he commended the cinematography and imagery, Muir stated that the film's inconsistent tone and lack of believable characters undermined the whole experience.{{sfn|Muir|2012|pp=134-136}}\n\nDonald Guarisco for [[AllMovie]] gave the film three and a half out of five stars, praising the acting and musical score. Guarisco added that ''Squirm'' was an \"excellent example of the 'revenge of nature' horror\" genre.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmovie.com/movie/squirm-v46341/review|title=Squirm (1976)|last=Guarisco|first=Donald|work=[[Allmovie]]|accessdate=August 7, 2019}}</ref> Film critic [[Leonard Maltin]] gave it three out of four stars, calling it an \"above-average horror outing [that] builds to good shock sequences\".{{sfn|Maltin|2013|p=1318}} [[TV Guide]], while giving it two out of four stars, said it was \"an underrated effort\" like Lieberman's other works.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tvguide.com/movies/squirm/review/118818/|title=Squirm Review|work=[[TV Guide]]|accessdate=August 7, 2019}}</ref> Jim Craddock, author of ''VideoHound's Golden Movie Retriever'', also gave two stars, calling it an \"okay\" giant worm movie.{{sfn|Craddock|2006|p=809}} In his book ''American International Pictures: A Comprehensive Filmography'', Rob Craig considered it to be \"an entertaining - and fairly insightful \u2212 film which is certainly not uncritical to its main characters and their community\". Craig also gave praise to Rick Baker's make-up effects.{{sfn|Craig|2019|page=349}} Kate Abbott for [[Time (magazine)|''Time'']] called it one of the best \"Killer-Animal Movies\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://entertainment.time.com/2010/08/20/top-10-killer-animal-movies/slide/squirm/|title=Top 10 Killer-Animal Movies|last=Abbott|first=Kate|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|page=6|date=August 19, 2010|accessdate=December 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Analysis==\n''Squirm'' can be seen as part of a tradition of 1970s \"revenge of nature\" films, the most important of which was ''[[Jaws (film)|Jaws]]''.{{sfn|Verevis|2016|p=102}}{{sfn|Platts|2015|pp=156-7}} This began in the early 1970s with films like ''[[Frogs (film)|Frogs]]'', ''[[Night of the Lepus]]'', and ''[[Sssssss]]'', leading on to ''Jaws'', ''Squirm'', ''[[Empire of the Ants (film)|Empire of the Ants]]'' and ''[[Kingdom of the Spiders]]''.{{sfn|Verevis|2016|p=102}} It can even be seen, along with other \"nature-running-amok thrillers\" of the latter half of the 1970s (like ''[[The Food of the Gods (film)|The Food of the Gods]]'', ''[[The Pack (1977 film)|The Pack]]'', ''[[The Car]]'', ''[[The Swarm (film)|The Swarm]]'', ''Empire of the Ants'', ''[[Long Weekend (1978 film)|Long Weekend]]'', and ''[[Day of the Animals]]''), as a \"''Jaws''ploitation\" film, a film [[exploitation film|exploiting]] the success of ''Jaws''.{{sfn|Hunter|2016|p=85}} The [[film studies]] scholar I. Q. Hunter disputes this, however, arguing that ''Jaws'' merely served to perpetuate the early-1970s genre that [[Quentin Tarantino]] called the \"Mother Nature goes ape-shit kind of movie\".{{sfn|Hunter|2016|p=85}} Muir calls ''Squirm'' one of the \"eco-horrors\" of the 1970s, along with ''Frogs'', ''Night of the Lepus'', ''Day of the Animals'', ''Kingdom of the Spiders'', ''Empire of the Ants'', ''The Swarm'', and ''[[Prophecy (film)|Prophecy]]''. These films reflected attitudes and fears prevalent at the time; specifically, they reflected the public's unease about what he called \"man's continued pillaging and pollution of the Earth\".{{sfn|Muir|2012|p=2}}\n\n[[Robin Wood (critic)|Robin Wood]] used ''Squirm'' as an example of nature films linking \"natural\" force to sexual and familiar tensions. Wood also expressed disappointment with the film's ending, as he felt the survival of Mick, Geri, and Alma counteracted the film's logic. He interpreted the film's world being \"totally overwhelmed by eruptions of devouring worms that develop, initially, out of familiar constraints and sexual possessiveness\".{{sfn|Wood|2018}} Kyle B. Counts notes similarities between ''Squirm'' and [[Straw Dogs (1971 film)|''Straw Dogs'']] in their themes of \"masculine ideals\". In both, the male leads play the hero. The reviewer, however, believed that the film did not give the impression that Don Scardino's character grew into a \"man\" after his experience.<ref name=Cinefantastique/>\n\nIn 2014, Liberman wrote a [[foreword]] for the book ''Subversive Horror Cinema: Countercultural Messages of Films from Frankenstein to the Present'' by Jon Towlson. In this, he addressed the critical and scholarly analysis of ''Squirm'':\n\n{{Cquote|quote=In my first movie, ''Squirm'' (1976), I really didn't try to make any sort of social or political comment. At least not consciously. However, soon after the movie's release, critics found some very profound subtexts which I myself wasn't aware of. Nature getting revenge on man for his disrespect of ecology. The symbolism of man's mortality and his inevitable fate of becoming worm food. Even themes of suppressed sexuality in the main characters. This could all very well be true, but if it is, it was not done purposely on my part.|author=[[Jeff Lieberman]]|source=''Subversive Horror Cinema: Countercultural Messages of Films from Frankenstein to the Present'' {{sfn|Towlson|2014|p=1}}}}\n\n==Legacy==\nDirector Brian De Palma included a poster of ''Squirm'' in several scenes of his 1981 film ''[[Blow Out]]''. Jeff Lieberman, who idolized De Palma, said in a ''[[Fangoria]]'' interview that he met the director years later and asked him about the poster. De Palma reportedly answered \"Only use the best!\"<ref name=\"Fangoria1993\"/> Pittsburgh musician [[Weird Paul Petroskey]] created an entire album, ''Worm in My Egg Cream'', dedicated to the \"worm in the egg cream\" scene and making extensive use of samples from the film. All 16 tracks on the album are titled \"Worm in My Egg Cream\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.weirdpaul.com/discography.html|title=THE MUSIC OF WEIRD PAUL|website=www.weirdpaul.com|access-date=April 11, 2017}}</ref>\n\n''Squirm'' was featured in a tenth-season episode of ''[[Mystery Science Theater 3000]]'' (''MST3K''), a comedy television series whose premise is that the character [[Mike Nelson (character)|Mike Nelson]] and his two robot friends [[Crow T. Robot]] and [[Tom Servo]] are forced to watch bad films as part of an ongoing scientific experiment. Broadcast on the [[Sci-Fi Channel]] on August 1, 1999, it was the penultimate episode to the series, ending with ''[[Danger: Diabolik]]'' a week later.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tvguide.com/tvshows/mystery-science-theater-3000/episodes/203329/|title=Mystery Science Theater 3000 Season 10 Episode Guide|work=[[TV Guide]]|accessdate=August 2, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"DVD\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dvdtalk.com/reviews/65514/mystery-science-theater-3000-the-turkey-day-collection-xxxi/|title=Mystery Science Theater 3000: The Turkey Day Collection|last=Sinnott|first=John|work=DVD Talk|date=November 25, 2014|accessdate=August 2, 2019}}</ref> It was shown along with the short film ''[[A Case of Spring Fever]]''.<ref name=\"DVD\"/> In response to the episode, Jeff Lieberman voiced his frustration towards the movie being sold to ''MST3K'', saying it cheapened the value of the movie.<ref name=\"BMD\">{{cite web|url=https://birthmoviesdeath.com/2013/08/14/why-the-director-of-squirm-was-furious-about-the-mst3k-version-of-his-movie|title=Why The Director Of SQUIRM Was Furious About The MST3K Version Of His Movie|last=Faraci|first=Devin|work=Birth.Movies.Death.|date=August 14, 2013|accessdate=August 4, 2019}}</ref> In 2014, Shout! Factory released the ''MST3K'' episode as part of the \"Turkey Day Collection\", along with episodes focused on ''[[Jungle Goddess]]'', ''[[The Painted Hills]]'', and ''[[The Screaming Skull]]''.<ref name=\"DVD\"/>\n\n==References==\n===Citations===\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Craddock|first=Jim|title=VideoHound's Golden Movie Retriever|date=2006|publisher=Gale Group|url-access=registration|isbn=0-7876-8980-7|url=https://archive.org/details/videohoundsgolde2006crad}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Craig|first=Rob|title=American International Pictures: A Comprehensive Filmography|date=2019|publisher=[[McFarland & Company]]|isbn=978-1-4766-6631-0|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=e0CIDwAAQBAJ}}\n*{{cite book|ref={{sfnref|Hunter|2016|p=85}}|author=I.Q. Hunter|title=Cult Film as a Guide to Life: Fandom, Adaptation, and Identity|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KaqaDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA85|date=8 September 2016|publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing|isbn=978-1-62356-381-3}}\n*{{cite book|ref={{sfnref|Maltin|2013|p=1318}}|last1=Maltin|first1=Leonard|last2=Carson|first2=Darwyn|title=Leonard Maltin's Movie Guide: The Modern Era|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780451418104|url-access=registration|year=2013|publisher=Signet|isbn=978-0-451-41810-4}}\n*{{cite book|ref={{sfnref|Muir|2012|pp=134-136}}|last=Muir|first=John|title=Horror Films of the 1970s|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ghmYvJReqIIC|date=November 22, 2012|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-0-7864-9156-8}}\n*{{cite book|last=Platts|first=Todd K.|year=2015|chapter=The New Horror Movie|editor1-last=Cogan|editor1-first=Brian|editor2-last=Gencarelli|editor2-first=Thom|title=Baby Boomers and Popular Culture|publisher=Praeger|ref=harv|pages=147-64}}\n*{{cite book|last=Towlson|first=Jon|title=Subversive Horror Cinema: Countercultural Messages of Films from Frankenstein to the Present|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RIgOAwAAQBAJ|date=2014|publisher=McFarland|isbn=147-6-6153-30}}\n*{{cite book|ref={{sfnref|Verevis|2016|p=102}}|last=Verevis|first=Constantine|chapter=Vicious cycle: ''Jaws'' and the revenge-of-nature films of the 1970s|editor1=Amanda Ann Klein|editor2=R. Barton Palmer|title=Cycles, Sequels, Spin-offs, Remakes, and Reboots: Multiplicities in Film and Television|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IvK4CwAAQBAJ&pg=PA102|date=March 15, 2016|publisher=University of Texas Press|isbn=978-1-4773-0817-2}}\n*{{cite book|last=Wood|first=Robin|year=2018|title=Robin Wood on the Horror Film: Collected Essays and Reviews|chapter=Return of the Repressed|publisher=[[Wayne State University Press]]|isbn=0-8143-4524-7|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lfRLDwAAQBAJ}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Amg title|46341|Squirm}}\n* {{AFI film|55262|Squirm}}\n* {{IMDb title|0075261|Squirm}}\n* {{tcmdb title|20595|Squirm}}\n\n{{Jeff Lieberman}}\n\n[[Category:1976 films]]\n[[Category:1976 horror films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American International Pictures films]]\n[[Category:American natural horror films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Jeff Lieberman]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Robert Prince]]\n[[Category:Films set in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Films featured on Mystery Science Theater 3000]]\n", "name_user": "GamerPro64", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRelease:minor", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Squirm"}
{"title_page": "You'll Never Walk Alone", "text_new": "{{Other uses|You'll Never Walk AGain(disambiguation)}}\n{{short description|1945 single from the musical Carousel}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2014}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = You'll Never Walk Alone\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| type       =\n| artist     =\n| album      =\n| EP         =\n| written    =\n| published  = 1945\n| released   =\n| format     =\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\u1eb6\n| genre      = [[Show tune]]\n| length     =\n| label      =\n| writer     =\n| composer   = [[Richard Rodgers]]\n| lyricist   = [[Oscar Hammerstein II]]\n| producer   =\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| title      =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\"'''You'll Never Walk Alone'''\" is a [[show tune]] from the 1945 [[Rodgers and Hammerstein]] musical ''[[Carousel (musical)|Carousel]]''. In the second act of the musical, Nettie Fowler, the cousin of the protagonist Julie Jordan, sings \"You'll Never Walk Alone\" to comfort and encourage Julie when her husband, Billy Bigelow, the male lead, falls on his knife and dies after a failed robbery attempt. It is [[reprise]]d in the final scene to encourage a graduation class of which Louise (Billy and Julie's daughter) is a member. The now invisible Billy, who has been granted the chance to return to Earth for one day in order to redeem himself, watches the ceremony and is able to silently motivate the unhappy Louise to join in the song.\n\nThe song is also sung at [[association football]] clubs around the world, where it is performed by a massed chorus of supporters on matchday; this tradition developed at [[Liverpool F.C.]] after the chart success of the 1963 single of the song by the local [[Liverpool]] group [[Gerry and the Pacemakers]].<ref name=\"Indy\"/>\n\n\"You'll Never Walk Alone\" has rapidly become the UK-wide anthem to show support for and encouragement to medical staff, first responders, those impacted by, under restrictions or in quarantine because of the [[2019-20 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite web |title=The classic hits that are now coronavirus anthems |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-52068546 |website=BBC News |date=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n[[Christine Johnson (actress)|Christine Johnson]], who created the role of Nettie Fowler, introduced the song in the original [[Broadway theater|Broadway]] production.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wlsUfOjVhrM |title=You'll Never Walk Alone (original version 1945) |work=Youtube |accessdate=April 20, 2011}}</ref>  Later in the show [[Jan Clayton]], as Julie Jordan, reprised it, with the chorus joining in.\n\nIn the film, it is first sung by [[Claramae Turner]] as Nettie. The weeping Julie Jordan ([[Shirley Jones]]) tries to sing it but cannot; it is later reprised by Julie and those attending the graduation.\n\n==Subsequent history==\nBesides the recordings of the song on the ''Carousel'' [[Cast recording|cast albums]] and the film soundtrack, the song has been recorded by many artists, with notable hit versions made by [[Roy Hamilton]],<ref name=pc3>{{Gilliland|url=https://digital.library.unt.edu/ark:/67531/metadc19748/m1/ |title=Show 3 - The Tribal Drum: The rise of rhythm and blues. [Part 1&#93; }}</ref> [[Frank Sinatra]], [[Roy Orbison]], [[Billy Eckstine]], [[Gerry and the Pacemakers]], [[Lee Towers]], [[Judy Garland]], [[Elvis Presley]], [[Johnny Cash]], [[Andy Williams]], [[Glen Campbell]], [[Johnny Maestro and The Brooklyn Bridge]], [[Olivia Newton-John]] and [[Doris Day]]. Progressive rock group [[Pink Floyd]] took a recording by the Liverpool [[Spion Kop (stadiums)|Kop]] choir, and \"interpolated\" it into their own song, \"[[Fearless (Pink Floyd song)|Fearless]]\", on their 1971 album ''[[Meddle]]''.\n\nFrom 1964 through 2010, [[Jerry Lewis]] concluded the annual [[The Jerry Lewis MDA Labor Day Telethon|Jerry Lewis Labor Day MDA Telethon]] by singing the song.<ref>\"Milestones: Retiring: Jerry Lewis\", ''Time'' magazine, May 30, 2011, p. 17</ref> After the end of a concert by the rock band [[Queen (band)|Queen]], the audience spontaneously sang this song, according to lead guitarist [[Brian May]],<ref>Interview with Tom Browne for BBC Radio One, broadcast Christmas Eve and Boxing Day 1977</ref> and this helped to inspire the creation of their songs \"[[We Are the Champions]]\" and  \"[[We Will Rock You]]\". Italian-American tenor [[Sergio Franchi]] sang a notable version accompanied by the Welsh Men's Choir on the 9 June 1968 telecast of ''The Ed Sullivan Show''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edsullivan.com/sofa-entertainment|title=SOFA Entertainment - Ed Sullivan Show|website=www.edsullivan.com}}</ref> He also covered this song in his 1964 RCA Victor album ''The Exciting Voice of Sergio Franchi.''\n\nIn 1990 at the [[Nelson Mandela: An International Tribute for a Free South Africa]] concert at [[Wembley Stadium]], London, the audience spontaneously broke out into a mass rendition. Mandela turned to [[Adelaide Tambo]] who accompanied him onto the stage and asked what the song was. She replied, \"A football song\".\n\nAmerican singer [[Barbra Streisand]] performed this song in a surprise appearance at the close of the [[53rd Primetime Emmy Awards|2001 Emmy Awards]], in honor of the victims of the [[September 11 attacks]].<ref>[https://www.usatoday.com/life/music/2001-12-12-streisandside.htm Streisand's stage fright spiked with thought of terror], By [[Edna Gundersen]], USA Today, December 12, 2001</ref> To mark the first anniversary of the attacks, [[Ren\u00e9e Fleming]] sang the song at the Concert for America.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2018/04/28/606716583/carousel-returns-to-broadway|title='Carousel' Returns To Broadway|accessdate=April 30, 2018|date=April 28, 2018|publisher=NPR|work=[[Weekend Edition Saturday]]|author=[[Scott Simon]]}}:\n\"SIMON: ... 'You'll Never Walk Alone' - you sang this at the Obama inauguration too, didn't you?\nFLEMING: Yes, and also the 9/11 memorial a year after the attacks.\"</ref> Fleming sang the song again at the [[First inauguration of Barack Obama|Inauguration of Barack Obama]] on January 20, 2009.<ref name=WAOTOIC>{{cite web|url=http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117939371.html?categoryid=1264&cs=1|title=We Are One: The Obama Inaugural Celebration|accessdate=February 8, 2009|date=January 18, 2009|publisher=RBI|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|author=Gallo, Phil}}</ref> \n \nIn 2010, the song was sung during the Last Night of [[the Proms]], with the choir at the [[Royal Albert Hall]] in London joined by crowds of the public from Hillsborough Castle, Northern Ireland; Caird Hall, Dundee; Hyde Park, London; Salford, Greater Manchester; and Wales, to mark the fiftieth anniversary of the death of Oscar Hammerstein II.<ref>{{cite news |title=Last Night: Last Night of the Proms, Royal Albert Hall, London |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/classical/reviews/last-night-last-night-of-the-proms-royal-albert-hall-london-2077560.html |accessdate=16 July 2019 |newspaper=The Independent}}</ref>\n\nIt has been the song of the [[Madison Scouts Drum and Bugle Corps]] song since 1954, where they first performed it as a part of their first field show in 1954. Challenged by the Rosemont [[The Cavaliers Drum and Bugle Corps|Cavaliers]] singing \"[[Over the Rainbow]]\" in 1957, the corps responded with \"You'll Never Walk Alone\", and it has been the official corps song ever since.\n\n[[Punk rock|Punk band]] [[Dropkick Murphys]] covered the song for their 2017 album ''[[11 Short Stories of Pain & Glory]]''. Vocalist/bassist [[Ken Casey]] said in a December 2016 interview discussing the reason behind their version. \"As you may know, [[opiate]] overdoses are an epidemic in America now particularly in (the [[Boston]]) area. I've been to thirty wakes in two years, three this week, one being my cousin, [[Al Barr|Al's]] lost a brother in law. It's hit home close to us. I was leaving one of the wakes and this song came on and as I was listening to the lyrics it summed up exactly how I was feeling. Sad, but knowing there is hope. You never have to be alone. I hope you like our version\".\n\n[[Lee Towers]] has been performing the song from an [[aerial work platform]] at the start of every [[Rotterdam Marathon]] since 1995.\n\n==Sporting anthem==\n\n===Liverpool F.C.===\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = You'll Never Walk Alone\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Gerry and the Pacemakers]]\n| album      = How Do You Like It\n| B-side     = \"It's All Right\"\n| released   = October 1963\n| format     = [[Gramophone record|7\"]]\n| recorded   = 2 July 1963\n| studio     = [[EMI Studios]], London<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britbands.bravepages.com/gerrydiary.html|title=Gerry's Datebook|website=www.britbands.bravepages.com}}</ref>\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Merseybeat]], [[baroque pop]]\n| length     = 2:40\n| label      = [[Columbia (EMI)]] (UK), [[Laurie Records]] (US)\n|writer=| composer   = [[Richard Rodgers]]\n| lyricist   = [[Oscar Hammerstein II]]\n| producer   = [[George Martin]]\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\nIn the UK, the song's most successful [[Cover version|cover]] was released in 1963 by the [[Liverpool|Liverpudlian]] [[Beat music|Merseybeat]] group [[Gerry and the Pacemakers]], peaking at number one on the UK singles chart for four consecutive weeks. Sung by Liverpool fans in 1963, the song quickly became the [[football song|football anthem]] of [[Liverpool F.C.]], which adopted \"You'll Never Walk Alone\" as its official motto on its [[coat of arms]]. The song is sung by its supporters moments before the start of each home game at [[Anfield]] with the Gerry and the Pacemakers version played over the [[public address system]].<ref name=\"Indy\" /><ref name=\"sport\">Nik Brumsack. [https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/news-and-comment/hillsborough-25th-anniversary-the-story-of-youll-never-walk-alone-9259702.html The story of 'You'll Never Walk Alone'], independent.co.uk, April 14, 2014.</ref><ref> {{YouTube|8AXxf52k0cE|Liverpool vs. Leeds United}}, F.A. Cup Final, BBC, 1965. \"The song was covered by Liverpool group Gerry & The Pacemakers in 1963. At this time, supporters standing on the Spion Kop terrace at Anfield began singing popular chart songs of the day. The mood was captured on camera by a BBC ''Panorama'' camera crew in 1964. One year later, when Liverpool faced Leeds in the cup final, the travelling Kop sang the same song and match commentator [[Kenneth Wolstenholme]] commended the 'Liverpool signature tune'.\" Paul Coslett, [https://www.bbc.co.uk/liverpool/content/articles/2008/06/09/youll_never_walk_alone_feature.shtml \u201cYou'll Never Walk Alone\u201d]. BBC Online. June 9, 2008.</ref> In 2013, the 50th anniversary of the song being sung on the Kop, Simon Hart of ''The Independent'' writes, \"Five decades on, the pre-match, scarfs-raised, sing-it-loud ritual is as much a part of Liverpool's fabric as their red shirts, its words written in wrought iron on the gates of their stadium.\"<ref name=\"Indy\" />\n\nAccording to former player [[Tommy Smith (footballer, born 1945)|Tommy Smith]], lead vocalist [[Gerry Marsden]] presented Liverpool manager [[Bill Shankly]] with a recording of his forthcoming cover single during a pre-season coach trip in the summer of 1963. \"Shanks was in awe of what he heard. ... Football writers from the local newspapers were travelling with our party and, thirsty for a story of any kind between games, filed copy back to their editors to the effect that we had adopted Gerry Marsden's forthcoming single as the club song.\"<ref>Smith, Tommy. ''Anfield Iron'', Bantam Press, p. 68-69</ref> The squad was subsequently invited to perform the track with the band on ''[[The Ed Sullivan Show]]'' with Marsden stating, \"Bill came up to me. He said, 'Gerry my son, I have given you a football team and you have given us a song'.\"<ref name=\"Indy\">{{cite news|last=Hart|first=Simon|title=Anfield's 50 years of never walking alone|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/news-and-comment/anfields-50-years-of-never-walking-alone-8905022.html|newspaper=The Independent|accessdate=6 April 2015|date=25 October 2013|quote=Gerry and the Pacemakers\u2019 version hit No 1 in October 1963, it was picked up by the Kop and the game\u2019s greatest anthem was born}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Shankly Gates.jpg|thumb|left|The 'Shankly Gates' entrance to Liverpool's home stadium [[Anfield]]]]\nShankly picked the song as his eighth and final selection for the BBC's ''[[Desert Island Discs]]'' on the eve of the [[1965 FA Cup Final]].<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/features/desert-island-discs/castaway/a805b634 \u201cBill Shankly, Desert island Discs\u201d]. BBC. Monday 26 April 1965.</ref> As Liverpool fans sang \"You'll Never Walk Alone\" at Wembley during the 1965 FA Cup Final win over Leeds, commentator [[Kenneth Wolstenholme]] referred to it as \"Liverpool's signature tune\".<ref name=\"FourFourTwo\">[http://www.fourfourtwo.com/features/why-liverpool-fans-sing-youll-never-walk-alone#QiSeISUZmHOwOU5L.99 Why Liverpool fans sing 'You'll Never Walk Alone']. ''[[FourFourTwo]]''. Retrieved 10 October 2016</ref> Marsden told BBC Radio how, in the 1960s, the [[disc jockey]] at Anfield would play the top ten commercial records in descending order, with the number one single played last, shortly before kickoff. [[Liverpool F.C.#Support|Liverpool fans on the Kop]] would sing along, but unlike with other hit singles, once \"You'll Never Walk Alone\" dropped out of the top ten, instead of disregarding the song, supporters continued to sing it.<ref>Cavanagh, John. \"The History of You'll Never Walk Alone\", BBC Songlines, 2006.</ref><ref>Morgan, John. \"The Other Mersey Sound\", BBC Panorama, 1964.</ref> In retirement, as his granddaughter Karen Gill recollects, Shankly would get out the gramophone and \u201cput the record on and play it, so we would hear it in the house.\u201d<ref name=\"Indy\" />\n\nIn his commentary on the memorial service following the [[Hillsborough disaster]] in 1989, [[Peter Jones (broadcaster)|Peter Jones]] recited the lyrics, which were then sung by a cathedral choir. [[Aretha Franklin]]'s recording of the song was played by [[John Peel]] in his first show following the disaster, when he became too upset to carry on broadcasting for a period. In 2019, during a [[Take That]] concert at Anfield, lead singer and Liverpool fan [[Gary Barlow]] brought out a guest vocalist, Gerry Marsden \u2013 who had come out of retirement for the performance \u2013 and they sang the club's anthem \u201cYou'll Never Walk Alone\u201d.<ref>{{cite news |title=Take That and Gerry Marsden bring Anfield to a standstill with heartwarming You'll Never Walk Alone |url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/whats-on/music-nightlife-news/take-that-anfield-special-ynwa-16391813 |accessdate=16 July 2019 |newspaper=Liverpool Echo}}</ref>\n\n===Other teams===\n\nThe song was adopted by Scottish team [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] after a 1966 [[Cup Winners Cup]] semi-final against Liverpool at Anfield, and is now sung by Celtic fans prior to every home [[UEFA competitions|European tie]],<ref name=\"Indy\"/><ref name=\"FourFourTwo\"/><ref name=\"Liverpool Celtic\">Aldred, Jessica. [http://football.guardian.co.uk/news/theknowledge/0,9204,912750,00.html Liverpool or Celtic: who Walked Alone first?] ''The Guardian''. March 12, 2003.</ref> and later by Germany's [[Borussia Dortmund]], which Liverpool went on to play in the cup final.<ref name=\"Indy\"/>\n\nThe song has also been adopted by Dutch team [[FC Twente]] after it was officially given to them by the Anfield stadium speaker George Sephton during the last game in the Diekman stadium, before moving to the new [[Arke Stadion]].<ref>Whyatt, Chris. [http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/7556749.stm McClaren's new charges] BBC. August 13, 2008.</ref> Today, Twente fans sing the song before every home game. Elsewhere in the Netherlands, [[Feyenoord]] and [[SC Cambuur]] have adopted the song as well.\n\nAdditional football teams which now use the song include [[1. FSV Mainz 05]], [[TSV 1860 Munich]], Belgium's [[Club Brugge KV]] and [[KV Mechelen]], Japan's [[F.C. Tokyo]],<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110319041142/http://mdn.mainichi.jp/mdnnews/sports/news/20110316p2g00m0sp093000c.html Nagatomo tells Japan \"You'll never walk alone\"], ''The mainichi Daily News''. March 2011.</ref> Spain's [[CD Lugo]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MguLkL0I-vg|title=\"You\u00b4ll never walk alone\" polo Anfield Carro PUNTO PELOTA|last=anfieldcarro|date=June 30, 2011|via=YouTube}}</ref> Greece's [[PAOK FC|PAOK]] and Indonesia's [[Bali United]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Chants|first1=North Side Boys 12|title=Bali United YNWA|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8OZkaHEVbfs|website=Youtube|publisher=Youtube|accessdate=1 May 2018}}</ref> In [[ice hockey]], the song has been adopted by German [[Deutsche Eishockey Liga]] side [[Krefeld Pinguine]] and [[KHL Medve\u0161\u010dak Zagreb|Croatian Medve\u0161\u010dak Zagreb]].\n\nA special recording of the song was made in solidarity with [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] following the [[Bradford City stadium fire|Valley Parade fire]] in 1985, when 56 spectators died and many more were seriously injured. The song was performed by [[The Crowd (band)|The Crowd]], which was a supergroup featuring Gerry Marsden, [[Paul McCartney]] and others, and spent two weeks at number one in the UK.\n\nSome years later, after witnessing a rendition of \"You'll Never Walk Alone\" at Anfield in 2007, the President of the [[Spanish Olympic Committee]], Alejandro Blanco, said he felt inspired to seek lyrics to his country's wordless national anthem, the [[Marcha Real]], ahead of [[Madrid bid for the 2016 Summer Olympics|Madrid's bid]] to host the [[2016 Summer Olympics|2016 Olympic Games]].<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20080202174214/http://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/070605/2/sufb.html Liverpool fans inspire Spain to write words to anthem], Reuters. June 5, 2005</ref><ref>[http://www.nbcnews.com/id/19442872 Spain to add lyrics to wordless national anthem], NBC News. June 26, 2007.</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2014 Hong Kong protests]], legislator [[Tam Yiu Chung]] quoted the song during a [[Legislative Council of Hong Kong]] meeting, to salute the Hong Kong Police,<ref>{{cite AV media|title=Legistrative Council Record|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xzcMQpxEm2w&t=1h43m30s}}</ref> who had received widespread criticism for using excessive force against pro-democracy protesters. More than 2,000 Liverpool Football Club fans in Hong Kong condemned his inappropriate use of the song, comparing his support of the police action to the police actions in the 1989 [[Hillsborough disaster]], where [[South Yorkshire Police]] were found to have distorted facts relating to the [[unlawful killing]] by negligence of 96 Liverpool supporters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xzcMQpxEm2w&t=1h43m30s|title=\u7acb\u6cd5\u6703\u6703\u8b70 (2014/10/16) - IV. \u7acb\u6cd5\u6703\u4f11\u6703\u5f85\u7e8c\u8b70\u6848 - \u6839\u64da\u300a\u8b70\u4e8b\u898f\u5247\u300b\u7b2c16(2)\u689d\u52d5\u8b70\u7684\u7acb\u6cd5\u6703\u4f11\u6703\u5f85\u7e8c\u8b70\u6848 (\u7b2c\u4e94\u90e8\u5206)|last=\u9999\u6e2f\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u7acb\u6cd5\u6703|date=October 16, 2014|via=YouTube}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://hk.news.yahoo.com/%E5%88%A9%E8%BF%B7%E8%81%AF%E7%BD%B2%E5%BC%B7%E7%83%88%E8%AD%B4%E8%B2%AC-%E8%AD%9A%E8%80%80%E5%AE%97%E5%8B%BF%E4%BE%AE%E8%BE%B1ynwa-120900475--sow.html|title=\u5229\u8ff7\u806f\u7f72\u5f37\u70c8\u8b74\u8cac\uff1a\u8b5a\u8000\u5b97\u52ff\u4fae\u8fb1YNWA - Yahoo\u5947\u6469\u65b0\u805e|publisher=}}</ref><ref>[http://webcast.legco.gov.hk/public/zh-hk/SearchResult?MeetingID=M14100067 Hong Kong Legislative Council Record 08:07:18 - 08:07:35]</ref>\n\nOn 13 March 2016, after [[Borussia Dortmund]]'s 2\u20130 win against [[1. FSV Mainz 05]] in the German [[Bundesliga]], supporters of both teams performed the song to commemorate a Dortmund fan who died from a [[cardiac arrest]] in the stands during the game.<ref>{{cite web|last=Whaling|first=James|title=Borussia Dortmund fan dies from heart attack during Bundesliga match against Mainz|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/borussia-dortmund-fan-dies-heart-7550808|work=[[Daily Mirror]]|date=13 March 2016|accessdate=14 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Marcus Mumford version==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = You'll Never Walk Alone\n| cover      = YoullNeverWalkAlone.png\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Marcus Mumford]]\n| album      = \n| released   = 20 March 2020\n| format     = {{hlist|[[Music download|Digital download]]|[[Streaming media|streaming]]}}\n| recorded   = \n| studio     =\n| genre      = \n| length     = 2:14\n| label      = [[Glassnote Records]]\n| writer     = \n| producer   = \n| prev_title = \n| prev_year  = \n| next_title = [[Lay Your Head on Me]]\n| next_year  = 2020\n| misc       = \n}}\nBritish singer, songwriter, musician, record producer and lead singer of the band [[Mumford & Sons]], [[Marcus Mumford]] released a cover version of the song as a single on 20 March 2020 through [[Glassnote Records]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/youll-never-walk-alone-single/1503802337|title=\u200eYou'll Never Walk Alone - Single by Marcus Mumford on Apple Music|publisher=[[Apple Music]]|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Background===\nAll proceeds from the song will be donated to the Grenfell Foundation and [[War Child (charity)|War Child UK]]. On his [[Instagram]] account, Mumford explained the idea behind releasing the song and revealing the charities that would benefit from sales of the song, \"It felt like we could get something out in the world that would benefit both of those organisations.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/marcus-mumford-shares-cover-of-youll-never-walk-alone-to-benefit-grenfell-foundation-2632920|title=Marcus Mumford covers 'You'll Never Walk Alone' to benefit Grenfell Foundation|publisher=[[NME]]|date=21 March 2020|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref> The song was in the works prior to the announcement of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|global coronavirus pandemic]] and was originally slated to air on a TV show in production, but \"for lots of reasons we wanted it just to be out in the world sooner rather than later, so here it is\", the singer shared on his [[YouTube]] account.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/9340760/marcus-mumford-youll-never-walk-alone|title=Marcus Mumford Covers Show Tune 'You'll Never Walk Alone' For a Good Cause: Listen|publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=23 March 2020|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Live performances===\nOn [[List of The Tonight Show Starring Jimmy Fallon episodes|1 April 2020]], Mumford performed the song from his home on American [[late-night talk show]] ''[[The Tonight Show Starring Jimmy Fallon]]''. The video was shot by his wife, [[Carey Mulligan]], he also explained why he released the song earlier than planned, \"This is a cover of 'You'll Never Walk Alone', which I had recorded in January for Jason Sudeikis, who I know well. I recorded it because I did the music for his TV show and we spoke and felt like it was appropriate to try and get it out sooner. We put it for two charities that are really close to my heart, War Child UK and the Grenfell Foundation, and also just to accompany people who might like it through a pretty weird time.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/marcus-mumford-lay-your-head-on-me-fallon-977090/|title=Watch Marcus Mumford Perform 'Lay Your Head on Me' on 'Fallon'|publisher=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=2 April 2020|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-sdqoufY9CQ|title=Marcus Mumford: You'll Never Walk Alone (Tonight Show: At Home Edition)|publisher=[[YouTube]]|date=1 April 2020|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2020)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br/>position\n|-\n{{single chart|Flanders Tip|30|artist=Marcus Mumford|song=You'll Never Walk Alone|rowheader=true|accessdate=18 April 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Scotland|72|date=20200327|rowheader=true|accessdate=8 April 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|UKdownload|72|date=20200327|rowheader=true|accessdate=8 April 2020}}\n|}\n\n==Recorded versions==\n{{div col|colwidth=}}\n*[[The Adicts]]<ref>{{cite web|author=John The Punk |url=http://adicts.us/adictsmusic.html |title=Welcome to The Adicts Official Website! |publisher=Adicts.us |accessdate=April 20, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110504130831/http://adicts.us/adictsmusic.html |archivedate=May 4, 2011 }}</ref>\n*[[Alfie Boe]] (\"Onward\") (2007)\n*[[Alicia Keys]] (''[[Hurricane Katrina disaster relief]]'', 2005)\n*[[Andr\u00e9 Rieu]] (2009 [[Maastricht]] concert)\n*[[Andy Williams]] (with orchestra conducted by Archie Bleyer)\n*[[Aretha Franklin]]  (1972, on the live album ''[[Amazing Grace (Aretha Franklin album)|Amazing Grace]]'')\n*[[Barry Manilow]] & [[Cilla Black]] (1993)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cillablack.com/music-youllneverwalkalone-single.htm | title=Cilla Black Discography: You'll Never Walk Alone (duet with Barry Manilow) \u2013 Single |accessdate=May 21, 2009}}</ref>\n*[[Bela B.]] & the Tikiwolves feat. Gary'o'Wolf (official [[FC St. Pauli]] Stadionhymn, 1992)\n*[[Bernadette Peters]]\n*[[Billy Eckstine]] (1960): Live album ''No Cover, No Minimum'', recorded in Las Vegas. Production was by Teddy Reig. The album was originally released by Roulette Records, but is also available on the Blue Note label.\n*[[Bryn Terfel]] (1996) \u2013 ''Something Wonderful: Bryn Terfel Sings Rodgers and Hammerstein''\n*[[Charice]] (2008)\n*[[Celtic Woman]] ([[Celtic Woman: Believe|Believe]] 2011) \n*[[Chris de Burgh]] (2008)\n*[[Christy Gibson]] (Thai Language Version) (2001) \u2013 ''Soo Yod Kao''\n*[[Christine Johnson (actress)|Christine Johnson]] on the Carousel Original Cast Album (1945)\n*[[Claramae Turner]] on the Carousel film soundtrack (1956)\n*[[The Crowd (band)|The Crowd]] (1985)\n*[[The Crusaders (1960s garage band)|The Crusaders]] (1966)\n*[[David Campbell (Australian musician)|David Campbell]] (2010)\n*[[David Phelps (musician)|David Phelps]] on the album ''Classic'' (2012)\n*[[Die Toten Hosen]] (2000, ''[[Bayern (song)|Bayern]]'' ep)\n*[[Dionne Warwick]] (1967, ''[[On Stage and in the Movies]]'' album track)\n*[[Doris Akers]] (1963)\n*[[Doris Day]] (on the ''[[You'll Never Walk Alone (Doris Day album)|You'll Never Walk Alone]]''  album) (1962)\n*[[Dropkick Murphys]] (appears on their album ''[[11 Short Stories of Pain & Glory]]'') (2017)\n*[[Dudu Fisher]] (2006)\n*[[Elha Nympha]] (2015, performed on the Live Semi-finals on the second season of [[The Voice Kids (Philippines season 2)|The Voice Kids]], and was moved to the grand finals)\n*[[Elvis Presley]] (1968 single release)\n*[[Engelbert Humperdinck (singer)|Engelbert Humperdinck]] (1972 album \"Live at the Riviera\", in Las Vegas)\n*[[The Flamingos]] (1960)\n*[[Frank Sinatra]] (1945) (1963)\n*[[Frankie Vaughan]] (1979)\n*[[Gene Vincent]] (1958) (''Gene Vincent Rocks and the Blue Caps Roll'' album track)\n*[[Gerry & The Pacemakers]] (1963)\n*[[Glen Campbell]] (1970)\n*[[Hayley Westenra]] (2001)\n*[[Il Divo]] (''[[A Musical Affair]]'', 2013)\n*[[Jackie Wilson]] (1965)\n*[[Jerry Reed]] (1971) (''Ko-Ko Joe'' album track)\n*[[Jo Stafford]] and [[Gordon MacRae]] (1963)\n*[[John Barrowman]] (2010) (''[[John Barrowman (album)|John Barrowman]]'' album track)\n*[[John Farnham]] (1998) - [[The Spirit of Christmas (compilation album)]]\n*[[John Gary]] (1965) on ''John Gary Sings Your All-Time Favorite Songs''\n*[[Johnny Cash]] (2003)\n*[[Johnny Preston]] (1960)\n*[[Johnny Maestro & the Brooklyn Bridge]] (1969)\n*[[Joseph Calleja]] (Last Night of the Proms, 2012)<ref>{{cite web|title=Richard Rogers: You'll Never Walk Alone - Last Night of the BBC Proms 2012|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=srPK4nDofto|publisher=BBC YouTube channel|accessdate=October 5, 2012|date=September 8, 2012}}</ref> \n*[[Josh Groban]] (2015)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/stages-deluxe-version/id972337386 |title=Stages \u2014 Josh Groban |work=iTunes Store |publisher=Apple Inc. |accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref>\n*[[Joyce DiDonato]] (2012)<ref>{{cite web|title=Joyce contributes to highly anticipated new recording: Rogers & Hammerstein at the Movies|url=http://www.joycedidonato.com/2012/08/22/joyce-contributes-to-highly-anticipated-new-recording-rogers-hammerstein-at-the-movies/|publisher=.joycedidonato.com|accessdate=October 5, 2012|date=August 22, 2012}}</ref> \n*[[Juan Diego Fl\u00f3rez]]  ([[Live 8]] \u2013 Berlin) (2005)\n*[[Judy Garland]] (1960)<ref>[http://www.jgdb.com/capstud.htm Recorded for Capitol Records] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080430042453/http://www.jgdb.com/capstud.htm |date=April 30, 2008 }} Judy Garland with Orchestra conducted, by Norrie Paramor, August 3, 1960.</ref>\n*[[Katherine Jenkins]] (2005)\n*[[Keith Jack]] (2008)\n*[[Kevin Rowland]] (1999)\n*[[Kiri Te Kanawa]] with the [[Mormon Tabernacle Choir]] (1990) \u2013 ''Songs of Inspiration''\n*[[The Knickerbockers]] (1966)\n*[[Lee Greenwood]]\n*[[Lee Towers]] (1976)<ref>[https://www.leetowers.nl/index.php/discografie-mainmenu-110 It's Raining In My Heart] (LP/MC) (Goud & Platina) 1976</ref>\n*[[The Lettermen]] (1964)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thelettermen.com/1960.html |title=You'll Never Walk Alone |publisher=Thelettermen.com |accessdate=April 20, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717011801/http://www.thelettermen.com/1960.html |archivedate=July 17, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n*[[Tammy Wynette]] (1969 Inspiration)\n*[[Liverpool F.C.]] (1977)  (FA Cup single: A-side - \"We Can Do It\" / \"Liverpool Lou\"  B-side - \"We Shall Not Be Moved\" / \"You'll Never Walk Alone\")\n*[[Los Fastidios]]\n*[[Louis Armstrong]] (1954) in a medley with [[Tenderly]]\n*[[Mahalia Jackson]]\n*[[Malena Ernman]] (2013)\n*[[Malcolm Vaughan]] (1959)\n*[[Marcus Mumford]] (2020)\n*[[Mark Knopfler]] (2018) incorporated an instrumental version into the track Just a Boy Away From Home on his album [[Down the Road Wherever]]\n*[[Mark Vincent]] (2010)\n*[[Mario Lanza]] (1952 and 1956)\n*[[Maureen Forrester]] on the Carousel MCA Classics album (1987)\n*[[Melanie C|Melanie Chisholm]] (2012)\n*[[Michael Crawford]] (1987)\n*[[Mormon Tabernacle Choir]] (1971)\n*[[Nina Simone]] (1958, ''[[Little Girl Blue (album)|Little Girl Blue]]'')\n*[[Olivia Newton-John]] (1989) \u2013 ''[[Warm and Tender (Olivia Newton-John album)|Warm and Tender]]''\n*[[Patricia Neway]] in the soundtrack of the 1967 television adaptation of ''Carousel'' (1967)\n*[[Patti Labelle & The Blue Belles]] (1964) - US #34\n*[[Patti LaBelle]] (1980's)\n*[[Pink Floyd]] (1971) \u2013 \"[[Fearless (Pink Floyd song)|Fearless]]\"\n*[[Pips, Chips & Videoclips]] (''[[Dernjava]]'' album, 1995)\n*[[The Priests]] (2009)\n*[[Perry Como]] (1951) (with Mitchell Ayres Orchestra)\n*[[Ray Charles]] (''[[Ingredients in a Recipe for Soul]]'' album track, July 1963)\n*[[Regine Velasquez]] (1989)\n*[[Ren\u00e9e Fleming]] (2003)\n*[[The Righteous Brothers]] (1965)\n*[[Riverdale Cast]] featuring main vocals of [[Madelaine Petsch]] (2018), appeared on ''[[Riverdale (2017 TV series)|Riverdale]]'' <ref>https://genius.com/Riverdale-cast-youll-never-walk-alone-lyrics</ref>\n*[[Robin S]] (appears on the 1998 movie soundtrack, ''[[Welcome to Woop Woop]]'')\n*[[Robson & Jerome]] (1996)\n*[[Roy Hamilton]] (1954)<ref name=pc3/>\n*[[Roy Orbison]] (1969) [[Sound recording and reproduction|recorded]] (2015) Released\n*[[Samuel Ramey]] (1989)\n*[[Sergio Franchi]] recorded on 1964 RCA album, ''The Exciting Voice of Sergio Franchi''\n*[[The Shadows]] (''[[Reflection (The Shadows album)|Reflection]]'' album track, 1990)\n*[[Shirley Bassey]] (1962, single B-side to \"Ave Maria\")<ref>''Columbia Catalog Number DB4816\"</ref>\n*[[Shirley Jones]] recorded it on the original movie soundtrack of ''Carousel'' and again on her 1989 album ''[[Silent Strength]]''\n*[[Sissel Kyrkjeb\u00f8]] (2004)\n*[[Smoking Popes]]\n*[[The Soldiers]] (2011)\n*[[Steven Houghton]] (1997) \u2013 ''Steven Houghton''\n*[[Susan Boyle]] (''[[Standing Ovation: The Greatest Songs from the Stage]]'', 2012)\n* Tape Toy (''[[2019-20 Coronavirus outbreak]]'', 2020)\n*[[The Three Tenors]] (''[[The Three Tenors: Paris 1998]]'', 1998)\n*[[Tokyo Ska Paradise Orchestra]] (2009) \u2013 ''Paradise Blue''\n*[[Tom Jones (singer)|Tom Jones]] (1969)\n*[[Trisha Yearwood]] (2016) - ''[[The Passion (U.S. TV special)|The Passion]]''\n*[[Vocal Majority]] (1997) \u2013 ''How Sweet the Sound''\n*[[Wayne Hussey]] and [[Julianne Regan]] (as [[Hussey-Regan]]) (2011) (in support of Liverpool F.C.'s disability charity, [[Respect 4 All]])<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/liverpoolfc#p/u/13/xy8MPNixmgI \"You'll Never Walk Alone\"]. Youtube.com (Liverpool FC's Channel). Retrieved December 27, 2011.</ref>\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|barbra-streisand|youll-never-walk-alone}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Rodgers and Hammerstein}}\n{{Liverpool F.C.}}\n{{Liliom}}\n{{Roy Hamilton}}\n{{The Bachelors}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:You'll Never Walk Alone}}\n[[Category:1945 songs]]\n[[Category:1964 singles]]\n[[Category:1985 singles]]\n[[Category:Songs with music by Richard Rodgers]]\n[[Category:Songs with lyrics by Oscar Hammerstein II]]\n[[Category:Songs from Rodgers and Hammerstein musicals]]\n[[Category:Shirley Jones songs]]\n[[Category:Gerry and the Pacemakers songs]]\n[[Category:Barbra Streisand songs]]\n[[Category:Labelle songs]]\n[[Category:Andy Williams songs]]\n[[Category:Jane Morgan songs]]\n[[Category:Johnny Preston songs]]\n[[Category:Glen Campbell songs]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by George Martin]]\n[[Category:Billboard Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs number-one singles]]\n[[Category:UK Singles Chart number-one singles]]\n[[Category:UK Independent Singles Chart number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Irish Singles Chart number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Liverpool F.C. songs]]\n[[Category:Feyenoord songs]]\n[[Category:Celtic F.C. songs]]\n[[Category:Charity singles]]\n[[Category:Football songs and chants]]\n[[Category:Protest songs]]\n[[Category:Mahalia Jackson songs]]\n[[Category:Roy Hamilton songs]]\n[[Category:Columbia Graphophone Company singles]]\n[[Category:Laurie Records singles]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Scotland]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses|You'll Never Walk Alone (disambiguation)}}\n{{short description|1945 single from the musical Carousel}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2014}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = You'll Never Walk Alone\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| type       =\n| artist     =\n| album      =\n| EP         =\n| written    =\n| published  = 1945\n| released   =\n| format     =\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\u1eb6\n| genre      = [[Show tune]]\n| length     =\n| label      =\n| writer     =\n| composer   = [[Richard Rodgers]]\n| lyricist   = [[Oscar Hammerstein II]]\n| producer   =\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| title      =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\"'''You'll Never Walk Alone'''\" is a [[show tune]] from the 1945 [[Rodgers and Hammerstein]] musical ''[[Carousel (musical)|Carousel]]''. In the second act of the musical, Nettie Fowler, the cousin of the protagonist Julie Jordan, sings \"You'll Never Walk Alone\" to comfort and encourage Julie when her husband, Billy Bigelow, the male lead, falls on his knife and dies after a failed robbery attempt. It is [[reprise]]d in the final scene to encourage a graduation class of which Louise (Billy and Julie's daughter) is a member. The now invisible Billy, who has been granted the chance to return to Earth for one day in order to redeem himself, watches the ceremony and is able to silently motivate the unhappy Louise to join in the song.\n\nThe song is also sung at [[association football]] clubs around the world, where it is performed by a massed chorus of supporters on matchday; this tradition developed at [[Liverpool F.C.]] after the chart success of the 1963 single of the song by the local [[Liverpool]] group [[Gerry and the Pacemakers]].<ref name=\"Indy\"/>\n\n\"You'll Never Walk Alone\" has rapidly become the UK-wide anthem to show support for and encouragement to medical staff, first responders, those impacted by, under restrictions or in quarantine because of the [[2019-20 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite web |title=The classic hits that are now coronavirus anthems |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-52068546 |website=BBC News |date=27 March 2020}}</ref> \n\n==Background==\n[[Christine Johnson (actress)|Christine Johnson]], who created the role of Nettie Fowler, introduced the song in the original [[Broadway theater|Broadway]] production.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wlsUfOjVhrM |title=You'll Never Walk Alone (original version 1945) |work=Youtube |accessdate=April 20, 2011}}</ref>  Later in the show [[Jan Clayton]], as Julie Jordan, reprised it, with the chorus joining in.\n\nIn the film, it is first sung by [[Claramae Turner]] as Nettie. The weeping Julie Jordan ([[Shirley Jones]]) tries to sing it but cannot; it is later reprised by Julie and those attending the graduation.\n\n==Subsequent history==\nBesides the recordings of the song on the ''Carousel'' [[Cast recording|cast albums]] and the film soundtrack, the song has been recorded by many artists, with notable hit versions made by [[Roy Hamilton]],<ref name=pc3>{{Gilliland|url=https://digital.library.unt.edu/ark:/67531/metadc19748/m1/ |title=Show 3 - The Tribal Drum: The rise of rhythm and blues. [Part 1&#93; }}</ref> [[Frank Sinatra]], [[Roy Orbison]], [[Billy Eckstine]], [[Gerry and the Pacemakers]], [[Lee Towers]], [[Judy Garland]], [[Elvis Presley]], [[Johnny Cash]], [[Andy Williams]], [[Glen Campbell]], [[Johnny Maestro and The Brooklyn Bridge]], [[Olivia Newton-John]] and [[Doris Day]]. Progressive rock group [[Pink Floyd]] took a recording by the Liverpool [[Spion Kop (stadiums)|Kop]] choir, and \"interpolated\" it into their own song, \"[[Fearless (Pink Floyd song)|Fearless]]\", on their 1971 album ''[[Meddle]]''.\n\nFrom 1964 through 2010, [[Jerry Lewis]] concluded the annual [[The Jerry Lewis MDA Labor Day Telethon|Jerry Lewis Labor Day MDA Telethon]] by singing the song.<ref>\"Milestones: Retiring: Jerry Lewis\", ''Time'' magazine, May 30, 2011, p. 17</ref> After the end of a concert by the rock band [[Queen (band)|Queen]], the audience spontaneously sang this song, according to lead guitarist [[Brian May]],<ref>Interview with Tom Browne for BBC Radio One, broadcast Christmas Eve and Boxing Day 1977</ref> and this helped to inspire the creation of their songs \"[[We Are the Champions]]\" and  \"[[We Will Rock You]]\". Italian-American tenor [[Sergio Franchi]] sang a notable version accompanied by the Welsh Men's Choir on the 9 June 1968 telecast of ''The Ed Sullivan Show''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edsullivan.com/sofa-entertainment|title=SOFA Entertainment - Ed Sullivan Show|website=www.edsullivan.com}}</ref> He also covered this song in his 1964 RCA Victor album ''The Exciting Voice of Sergio Franchi.''\n\nIn 1990 at the [[Nelson Mandela: An International Tribute for a Free South Africa]] concert at [[Wembley Stadium]], London, the audience spontaneously broke out into a mass rendition. Mandela turned to [[Adelaide Tambo]] who accompanied him onto the stage and asked what the song was. She replied, \"A football song\".\n\nAmerican singer [[Barbra Streisand]] performed this song in a surprise appearance at the close of the [[53rd Primetime Emmy Awards|2001 Emmy Awards]], in honor of the victims of the [[September 11 attacks]].<ref>[https://www.usatoday.com/life/music/2001-12-12-streisandside.htm Streisand's stage fright spiked with thought of terror], By [[Edna Gundersen]], USA Today, December 12, 2001</ref> To mark the first anniversary of the attacks, [[Ren\u00e9e Fleming]] sang the song at the Concert for America.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2018/04/28/606716583/carousel-returns-to-broadway|title='Carousel' Returns To Broadway|accessdate=April 30, 2018|date=April 28, 2018|publisher=NPR|work=[[Weekend Edition Saturday]]|author=[[Scott Simon]]}}:\n\"SIMON: ... 'You'll Never Walk Alone' - you sang this at the Obama inauguration too, didn't you?\nFLEMING: Yes, and also the 9/11 memorial a year after the attacks.\"</ref> Fleming sang the song again at the [[First inauguration of Barack Obama|Inauguration of Barack Obama]] on January 20, 2009.<ref name=WAOTOIC>{{cite web|url=http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117939371.html?categoryid=1264&cs=1|title=We Are One: The Obama Inaugural Celebration|accessdate=February 8, 2009|date=January 18, 2009|publisher=RBI|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|author=Gallo, Phil}}</ref> \n \nIn 2010, the song was sung during the Last Night of [[the Proms]], with the choir at the [[Royal Albert Hall]] in London joined by crowds of the public from Hillsborough Castle, Northern Ireland; Caird Hall, Dundee; Hyde Park, London; Salford, Greater Manchester; and Wales, to mark the fiftieth anniversary of the death of Oscar Hammerstein II.<ref>{{cite news |title=Last Night: Last Night of the Proms, Royal Albert Hall, London |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/classical/reviews/last-night-last-night-of-the-proms-royal-albert-hall-london-2077560.html |accessdate=16 July 2019 |newspaper=The Independent}}</ref>\n\nIt has been the song of the [[Madison Scouts Drum and Bugle Corps]] song since 1954, where they first performed it as a part of their first field show in 1954. Challenged by the Rosemont [[The Cavaliers Drum and Bugle Corps|Cavaliers]] singing \"[[Over the Rainbow]]\" in 1957, the corps responded with \"You'll Never Walk Alone\", and it has been the official corps song ever since.\n\n[[Punk rock|Punk band]] [[Dropkick Murphys]] covered the song for their 2017 album ''[[11 Short Stories of Pain & Glory]]''. Vocalist/bassist [[Ken Casey]] said in a December 2016 interview discussing the reason behind their version. \"As you may know, [[opiate]] overdoses are an epidemic in America now particularly in (the [[Boston]]) area. I've been to thirty wakes in two years, three this week, one being my cousin, [[Al Barr|Al's]] lost a brother in law. It's hit home close to us. I was leaving one of the wakes and this song came on and as I was listening to the lyrics it summed up exactly how I was feeling. Sad, but knowing there is hope. You never have to be alone. I hope you like our version\".\n\n[[Lee Towers]] has been performing the song from an [[aerial work platform]] at the start of every [[Rotterdam Marathon]] since 1995.\n\n==Sporting anthem==\n\n===Liverpool F.C.===\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = You'll Never Walk Alone\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Gerry and the Pacemakers]]\n| album      = How Do You Like It\n| B-side     = \"It's All Right\"\n| released   = October 1963\n| format     = [[Gramophone record|7\"]]\n| recorded   = 2 July 1963\n| studio     = [[EMI Studios]], London<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britbands.bravepages.com/gerrydiary.html|title=Gerry's Datebook|website=www.britbands.bravepages.com}}</ref>\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Merseybeat]], [[baroque pop]]\n| length     = 2:40\n| label      = [[Columbia (EMI)]] (UK), [[Laurie Records]] (US)\n|writer=| composer   = [[Richard Rodgers]]\n| lyricist   = [[Oscar Hammerstein II]]\n| producer   = [[George Martin]]\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\nIn the UK, the song's most successful [[Cover version|cover]] was released in 1963 by the [[Liverpool|Liverpudlian]] [[Beat music|Merseybeat]] group [[Gerry and the Pacemakers]], peaking at number one on the UK singles chart for four consecutive weeks. Sung by Liverpool fans in 1963, the song quickly became the [[football song|football anthem]] of [[Liverpool F.C.]], which adopted \"You'll Never Walk Alone\" as its official motto on its [[coat of arms]]. The song is sung by its supporters moments before the start of each home game at [[Anfield]] with the Gerry and the Pacemakers version played over the [[public address system]].<ref name=\"Indy\" /><ref name=\"sport\">Nik Brumsack. [https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/news-and-comment/hillsborough-25th-anniversary-the-story-of-youll-never-walk-alone-9259702.html The story of 'You'll Never Walk Alone'], independent.co.uk, April 14, 2014.</ref><ref> {{YouTube|8AXxf52k0cE|Liverpool vs. Leeds United}}, F.A. Cup Final, BBC, 1965. \"The song was covered by Liverpool group Gerry & The Pacemakers in 1963. At this time, supporters standing on the Spion Kop terrace at Anfield began singing popular chart songs of the day. The mood was captured on camera by a BBC ''Panorama'' camera crew in 1964. One year later, when Liverpool faced Leeds in the cup final, the travelling Kop sang the same song and match commentator [[Kenneth Wolstenholme]] commended the 'Liverpool signature tune'.\" Paul Coslett, [https://www.bbc.co.uk/liverpool/content/articles/2008/06/09/youll_never_walk_alone_feature.shtml \u201cYou'll Never Walk Alone\u201d]. BBC Online. June 9, 2008.</ref> In 2013, the 50th anniversary of the song being sung on the Kop, Simon Hart of ''The Independent'' writes, \"Five decades on, the pre-match, scarfs-raised, sing-it-loud ritual is as much a part of Liverpool's fabric as their red shirts, its words written in wrought iron on the gates of their stadium.\"<ref name=\"Indy\" />\n\nAccording to former player [[Tommy Smith (footballer, born 1945)|Tommy Smith]], lead vocalist [[Gerry Marsden]] presented Liverpool manager [[Bill Shankly]] with a recording of his forthcoming cover single during a pre-season coach trip in the summer of 1963. \"Shanks was in awe of what he heard. ... Football writers from the local newspapers were travelling with our party and, thirsty for a story of any kind between games, filed copy back to their editors to the effect that we had adopted Gerry Marsden's forthcoming single as the club song.\"<ref>Smith, Tommy. ''Anfield Iron'', Bantam Press, p. 68-69</ref> The squad was subsequently invited to perform the track with the band on ''[[The Ed Sullivan Show]]'' with Marsden stating, \"Bill came up to me. He said, 'Gerry my son, I have given you a football team and you have given us a song'.\"<ref name=\"Indy\">{{cite news|last=Hart|first=Simon|title=Anfield's 50 years of never walking alone|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/news-and-comment/anfields-50-years-of-never-walking-alone-8905022.html|newspaper=The Independent|accessdate=6 April 2015|date=25 October 2013|quote=Gerry and the Pacemakers\u2019 version hit No 1 in October 1963, it was picked up by the Kop and the game\u2019s greatest anthem was born}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Shankly Gates.jpg|thumb|left|The 'Shankly Gates' entrance to Liverpool's home stadium [[Anfield]]]]\nShankly picked the song as his eighth and final selection for the BBC's ''[[Desert Island Discs]]'' on the eve of the [[1965 FA Cup Final]].<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/features/desert-island-discs/castaway/a805b634 \u201cBill Shankly, Desert island Discs\u201d]. BBC. Monday 26 April 1965.</ref> As Liverpool fans sang \"You'll Never Walk Alone\" at Wembley during the 1965 FA Cup Final win over Leeds, commentator [[Kenneth Wolstenholme]] referred to it as \"Liverpool's signature tune\".<ref name=\"FourFourTwo\">[http://www.fourfourtwo.com/features/why-liverpool-fans-sing-youll-never-walk-alone#QiSeISUZmHOwOU5L.99 Why Liverpool fans sing 'You'll Never Walk Alone']. ''[[FourFourTwo]]''. Retrieved 10 October 2016</ref> Marsden told BBC Radio how, in the 1960s, the [[disc jockey]] at Anfield would play the top ten commercial records in descending order, with the number one single played last, shortly before kickoff. [[Liverpool F.C.#Support|Liverpool fans on the Kop]] would sing along, but unlike with other hit singles, once \"You'll Never Walk Alone\" dropped out of the top ten, instead of disregarding the song, supporters continued to sing it.<ref>Cavanagh, John. \"The History of You'll Never Walk Alone\", BBC Songlines, 2006.</ref><ref>Morgan, John. \"The Other Mersey Sound\", BBC Panorama, 1964.</ref> In retirement, as his granddaughter Karen Gill recollects, Shankly would get out the gramophone and \u201cput the record on and play it, so we would hear it in the house.\u201d<ref name=\"Indy\" />\n\nIn his commentary on the memorial service following the [[Hillsborough disaster]] in 1989, [[Peter Jones (broadcaster)|Peter Jones]] recited the lyrics, which were then sung by a cathedral choir. [[Aretha Franklin]]'s recording of the song was played by [[John Peel]] in his first show following the disaster, when he became too upset to carry on broadcasting for a period. In 2019, during a [[Take That]] concert at Anfield, lead singer and Liverpool fan [[Gary Barlow]] brought out a guest vocalist, Gerry Marsden \u2013 who had come out of retirement for the performance \u2013 and they sang the club's anthem \u201cYou'll Never Walk Alone\u201d.<ref>{{cite news |title=Take That and Gerry Marsden bring Anfield to a standstill with heartwarming You'll Never Walk Alone |url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/whats-on/music-nightlife-news/take-that-anfield-special-ynwa-16391813 |accessdate=16 July 2019 |newspaper=Liverpool Echo}}</ref>\n\n===Other teams===\n\nThe song was adopted by Scottish team [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] after a 1966 [[Cup Winners Cup]] semi-final against Liverpool at Anfield, and is now sung by Celtic fans prior to every home [[UEFA competitions|European tie]],<ref name=\"Indy\"/><ref name=\"FourFourTwo\"/><ref name=\"Liverpool Celtic\">Aldred, Jessica. [http://football.guardian.co.uk/news/theknowledge/0,9204,912750,00.html Liverpool or Celtic: who Walked Alone first?] ''The Guardian''. March 12, 2003.</ref> and later by Germany's [[Borussia Dortmund]], which Liverpool went on to play in the cup final.<ref name=\"Indy\"/>\n\nThe song has also been adopted by Dutch team [[FC Twente]] after it was officially given to them by the Anfield stadium speaker George Sephton during the last game in the Diekman stadium, before moving to the new [[Arke Stadion]].<ref>Whyatt, Chris. [http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/7556749.stm McClaren's new charges] BBC. August 13, 2008.</ref> Today, Twente fans sing the song before every home game. Elsewhere in the Netherlands, [[Feyenoord]] and [[SC Cambuur]] have adopted the song as well.\n\nAdditional football teams which now use the song include [[1. FSV Mainz 05]], [[TSV 1860 Munich]], Belgium's [[Club Brugge KV]] and [[KV Mechelen]], Japan's [[F.C. Tokyo]],<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110319041142/http://mdn.mainichi.jp/mdnnews/sports/news/20110316p2g00m0sp093000c.html Nagatomo tells Japan \"You'll never walk alone\"], ''The mainichi Daily News''. March 2011.</ref> Spain's [[CD Lugo]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MguLkL0I-vg|title=\"You\u00b4ll never walk alone\" polo Anfield Carro PUNTO PELOTA|last=anfieldcarro|date=June 30, 2011|via=YouTube}}</ref> Greece's [[PAOK FC|PAOK]] and Indonesia's [[Bali United]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Chants|first1=North Side Boys 12|title=Bali United YNWA|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8OZkaHEVbfs|website=Youtube|publisher=Youtube|accessdate=1 May 2018}}</ref> In [[ice hockey]], the song has been adopted by German [[Deutsche Eishockey Liga]] side [[Krefeld Pinguine]] and [[KHL Medve\u0161\u010dak Zagreb|Croatian Medve\u0161\u010dak Zagreb]].\n\nA special recording of the song was made in solidarity with [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] following the [[Bradford City stadium fire|Valley Parade fire]] in 1985, when 56 spectators died and many more were seriously injured. The song was performed by [[The Crowd (band)|The Crowd]], which was a supergroup featuring Gerry Marsden, [[Paul McCartney]] and others, and spent two weeks at number one in the UK.\n\nSome years later, after witnessing a rendition of \"You'll Never Walk Alone\" at Anfield in 2007, the President of the [[Spanish Olympic Committee]], Alejandro Blanco, said he felt inspired to seek lyrics to his country's wordless national anthem, the [[Marcha Real]], ahead of [[Madrid bid for the 2016 Summer Olympics|Madrid's bid]] to host the [[2016 Summer Olympics|2016 Olympic Games]].<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20080202174214/http://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/070605/2/sufb.html Liverpool fans inspire Spain to write words to anthem], Reuters. June 5, 2005</ref><ref>[http://www.nbcnews.com/id/19442872 Spain to add lyrics to wordless national anthem], NBC News. June 26, 2007.</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2014 Hong Kong protests]], legislator [[Tam Yiu Chung]] quoted the song during a [[Legislative Council of Hong Kong]] meeting, to salute the Hong Kong Police,<ref>{{cite AV media|title=Legistrative Council Record|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xzcMQpxEm2w&t=1h43m30s}}</ref> who had received widespread criticism for using excessive force against pro-democracy protesters. More than 2,000 Liverpool Football Club fans in Hong Kong condemned his inappropriate use of the song, comparing his support of the police action to the police actions in the 1989 [[Hillsborough disaster]], where [[South Yorkshire Police]] were found to have distorted facts relating to the [[unlawful killing]] by negligence of 96 Liverpool supporters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xzcMQpxEm2w&t=1h43m30s|title=\u7acb\u6cd5\u6703\u6703\u8b70 (2014/10/16) - IV. \u7acb\u6cd5\u6703\u4f11\u6703\u5f85\u7e8c\u8b70\u6848 - \u6839\u64da\u300a\u8b70\u4e8b\u898f\u5247\u300b\u7b2c16(2)\u689d\u52d5\u8b70\u7684\u7acb\u6cd5\u6703\u4f11\u6703\u5f85\u7e8c\u8b70\u6848 (\u7b2c\u4e94\u90e8\u5206)|last=\u9999\u6e2f\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u7acb\u6cd5\u6703|date=October 16, 2014|via=YouTube}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://hk.news.yahoo.com/%E5%88%A9%E8%BF%B7%E8%81%AF%E7%BD%B2%E5%BC%B7%E7%83%88%E8%AD%B4%E8%B2%AC-%E8%AD%9A%E8%80%80%E5%AE%97%E5%8B%BF%E4%BE%AE%E8%BE%B1ynwa-120900475--sow.html|title=\u5229\u8ff7\u806f\u7f72\u5f37\u70c8\u8b74\u8cac\uff1a\u8b5a\u8000\u5b97\u52ff\u4fae\u8fb1YNWA - Yahoo\u5947\u6469\u65b0\u805e|publisher=}}</ref><ref>[http://webcast.legco.gov.hk/public/zh-hk/SearchResult?MeetingID=M14100067 Hong Kong Legislative Council Record 08:07:18 - 08:07:35]</ref>\n\nOn 13 March 2016, after [[Borussia Dortmund]]'s 2\u20130 win against [[1. FSV Mainz 05]] in the German [[Bundesliga]], supporters of both teams performed the song to commemorate a Dortmund fan who died from a [[cardiac arrest]] in the stands during the game.<ref>{{cite web|last=Whaling|first=James|title=Borussia Dortmund fan dies from heart attack during Bundesliga match against Mainz|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/borussia-dortmund-fan-dies-heart-7550808|work=[[Daily Mirror]]|date=13 March 2016|accessdate=14 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Marcus Mumford version==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = You'll Never Walk Alone\n| cover      = YoullNeverWalkAlone.png\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Marcus Mumford]]\n| album      = \n| released   = 20 March 2020\n| format     = {{hlist|[[Music download|Digital download]]|[[Streaming media|streaming]]}}\n| recorded   = \n| studio     =\n| genre      = \n| length     = 2:14\n| label      = [[Glassnote Records]]\n| writer     = \n| producer   = \n| prev_title = \n| prev_year  = \n| next_title = [[Lay Your Head on Me]]\n| next_year  = 2020\n| misc       = \n}}\nBritish singer, songwriter, musician, record producer and lead singer of the band [[Mumford & Sons]], [[Marcus Mumford]] released a cover version of the song as a single on 20 March 2020 through [[Glassnote Records]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/youll-never-walk-alone-single/1503802337|title=\u200eYou'll Never Walk Alone - Single by Marcus Mumford on Apple Music|publisher=[[Apple Music]]|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Background===\nAll proceeds from the song will be donated to the Grenfell Foundation and [[War Child (charity)|War Child UK]]. On his [[Instagram]] account, Mumford explained the idea behind releasing the song and revealing the charities that would benefit from sales of the song, \"It felt like we could get something out in the world that would benefit both of those organisations.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/marcus-mumford-shares-cover-of-youll-never-walk-alone-to-benefit-grenfell-foundation-2632920|title=Marcus Mumford covers 'You'll Never Walk Alone' to benefit Grenfell Foundation|publisher=[[NME]]|date=21 March 2020|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref> The song was in the works prior to the announcement of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|global coronavirus pandemic]] and was originally slated to air on a TV show in production, but \"for lots of reasons we wanted it just to be out in the world sooner rather than later, so here it is\", the singer shared on his [[YouTube]] account.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/9340760/marcus-mumford-youll-never-walk-alone|title=Marcus Mumford Covers Show Tune 'You'll Never Walk Alone' For a Good Cause: Listen|publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=23 March 2020|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Live performances===\nOn [[List of The Tonight Show Starring Jimmy Fallon episodes|1 April 2020]], Mumford performed the song from his home on American [[late-night talk show]] ''[[The Tonight Show Starring Jimmy Fallon]]''. The video was shot by his wife, [[Carey Mulligan]], he also explained why he released the song earlier than planned, \"This is a cover of 'You'll Never Walk Alone', which I had recorded in January for Jason Sudeikis, who I know well. I recorded it because I did the music for his TV show and we spoke and felt like it was appropriate to try and get it out sooner. We put it for two charities that are really close to my heart, War Child UK and the Grenfell Foundation, and also just to accompany people who might like it through a pretty weird time.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/marcus-mumford-lay-your-head-on-me-fallon-977090/|title=Watch Marcus Mumford Perform 'Lay Your Head on Me' on 'Fallon'|publisher=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=2 April 2020|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-sdqoufY9CQ|title=Marcus Mumford: You'll Never Walk Alone (Tonight Show: At Home Edition)|publisher=[[YouTube]]|date=1 April 2020|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2020)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br/>position\n|-\n{{single chart|Flanders Tip|30|artist=Marcus Mumford|song=You'll Never Walk Alone|rowheader=true|accessdate=18 April 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Scotland|72|date=20200327|rowheader=true|accessdate=8 April 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|UKdownload|72|date=20200327|rowheader=true|accessdate=8 April 2020}}\n|}\n\n==Recorded versions==\n{{div col|colwidth=}}\n*[[The Adicts]]<ref>{{cite web|author=John The Punk |url=http://adicts.us/adictsmusic.html |title=Welcome to The Adicts Official Website! |publisher=Adicts.us |accessdate=April 20, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110504130831/http://adicts.us/adictsmusic.html |archivedate=May 4, 2011 }}</ref>\n*[[Alfie Boe]] (\"Onward\") (2007)\n*[[Alicia Keys]] (''[[Hurricane Katrina disaster relief]]'', 2005)\n*[[Andr\u00e9 Rieu]] (2009 [[Maastricht]] concert)\n*[[Andy Williams]] (with orchestra conducted by Archie Bleyer)\n*[[Aretha Franklin]]  (1972, on the live album ''[[Amazing Grace (Aretha Franklin album)|Amazing Grace]]'')\n*[[Barry Manilow]] & [[Cilla Black]] (1993)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cillablack.com/music-youllneverwalkalone-single.htm | title=Cilla Black Discography: You'll Never Walk Alone (duet with Barry Manilow) \u2013 Single |accessdate=May 21, 2009}}</ref>\n*[[Bela B.]] & the Tikiwolves feat. Gary'o'Wolf (official [[FC St. Pauli]] Stadionhymn, 1992)\n*[[Bernadette Peters]]\n*[[Billy Eckstine]] (1960): Live album ''No Cover, No Minimum'', recorded in Las Vegas. Production was by Teddy Reig. The album was originally released by Roulette Records, but is also available on the Blue Note label.\n*[[Bryn Terfel]] (1996) \u2013 ''Something Wonderful: Bryn Terfel Sings Rodgers and Hammerstein''\n*[[Charice]] (2008)\n*[[Celtic Woman]] ([[Celtic Woman: Believe|Believe]] 2011) \n*[[Chris de Burgh]] (2008)\n*[[Christy Gibson]] (Thai Language Version) (2001) \u2013 ''Soo Yod Kao''\n*[[Christine Johnson (actress)|Christine Johnson]] on the Carousel Original Cast Album (1945)\n*[[Claramae Turner]] on the Carousel film soundtrack (1956)\n*[[The Crowd (band)|The Crowd]] (1985)\n*[[The Crusaders (1960s garage band)|The Crusaders]] (1966)\n*[[David Campbell (Australian musician)|David Campbell]] (2010)\n*[[David Phelps (musician)|David Phelps]] on the album ''Classic'' (2012)\n*[[Die Toten Hosen]] (2000, ''[[Bayern (song)|Bayern]]'' ep)\n*[[Dionne Warwick]] (1967, ''[[On Stage and in the Movies]]'' album track)\n*[[Doris Akers]] (1963)\n*[[Doris Day]] (on the ''[[You'll Never Walk Alone (Doris Day album)|You'll Never Walk Alone]]''  album) (1962)\n*[[Dropkick Murphys]] (appears on their album ''[[11 Short Stories of Pain & Glory]]'') (2017)\n*[[Dudu Fisher]] (2006)\n*[[Elha Nympha]] (2015, performed on the Live Semi-finals on the second season of [[The Voice Kids (Philippines season 2)|The Voice Kids]], and was moved to the grand finals)\n*[[Elvis Presley]] (1968 single release)\n*[[Engelbert Humperdinck (singer)|Engelbert Humperdinck]] (1972 album \"Live at the Riviera\", in Las Vegas)\n*[[The Flamingos]] (1960)\n*[[Frank Sinatra]] (1945) (1963)\n*[[Frankie Vaughan]] (1979)\n*[[Gene Vincent]] (1958) (''Gene Vincent Rocks and the Blue Caps Roll'' album track)\n*[[Gerry & The Pacemakers]] (1963)\n*[[Glen Campbell]] (1970)\n*[[Hayley Westenra]] (2001)\n*[[Il Divo]] (''[[A Musical Affair]]'', 2013)\n*[[Jackie Wilson]] (1965)\n*[[Jerry Reed]] (1971) (''Ko-Ko Joe'' album track)\n*[[Jo Stafford]] and [[Gordon MacRae]] (1963)\n*[[John Barrowman]] (2010) (''[[John Barrowman (album)|John Barrowman]]'' album track)\n*[[John Farnham]] (1998) - [[The Spirit of Christmas (compilation album)]]\n*[[John Gary]] (1965) on ''John Gary Sings Your All-Time Favorite Songs''\n*[[Johnny Cash]] (2003)\n*[[Johnny Preston]] (1960)\n*[[Johnny Maestro & the Brooklyn Bridge]] (1969)\n*[[Joseph Calleja]] (Last Night of the Proms, 2012)<ref>{{cite web|title=Richard Rogers: You'll Never Walk Alone - Last Night of the BBC Proms 2012|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=srPK4nDofto|publisher=BBC YouTube channel|accessdate=October 5, 2012|date=September 8, 2012}}</ref> \n*[[Josh Groban]] (2015)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/stages-deluxe-version/id972337386 |title=Stages \u2014 Josh Groban |work=iTunes Store |publisher=Apple Inc. |accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref>\n*[[Joyce DiDonato]] (2012)<ref>{{cite web|title=Joyce contributes to highly anticipated new recording: Rogers & Hammerstein at the Movies|url=http://www.joycedidonato.com/2012/08/22/joyce-contributes-to-highly-anticipated-new-recording-rogers-hammerstein-at-the-movies/|publisher=.joycedidonato.com|accessdate=October 5, 2012|date=August 22, 2012}}</ref> \n*[[Juan Diego Fl\u00f3rez]]  ([[Live 8]] \u2013 Berlin) (2005)\n*[[Judy Garland]] (1960)<ref>[http://www.jgdb.com/capstud.htm Recorded for Capitol Records] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080430042453/http://www.jgdb.com/capstud.htm |date=April 30, 2008 }} Judy Garland with Orchestra conducted, by Norrie Paramor, August 3, 1960.</ref>\n*[[Katherine Jenkins]] (2005)\n*[[Keith Jack]] (2008)\n*[[Kevin Rowland]] (1999)\n*[[Kiri Te Kanawa]] with the [[Mormon Tabernacle Choir]] (1990) \u2013 ''Songs of Inspiration''\n*[[The Knickerbockers]] (1966)\n*[[Lee Greenwood]]\n*[[Lee Towers]] (1976)<ref>[https://www.leetowers.nl/index.php/discografie-mainmenu-110 It's Raining In My Heart] (LP/MC) (Goud & Platina) 1976</ref>\n*[[The Lettermen]] (1964)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thelettermen.com/1960.html |title=You'll Never Walk Alone |publisher=Thelettermen.com |accessdate=April 20, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717011801/http://www.thelettermen.com/1960.html |archivedate=July 17, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n*[[Tammy Wynette]] (1969 Inspiration)\n*[[Liverpool F.C.]] (1977)  (FA Cup single: A-side - \"We Can Do It\" / \"Liverpool Lou\"  B-side - \"We Shall Not Be Moved\" / \"You'll Never Walk Alone\")\n*[[Los Fastidios]]\n*[[Louis Armstrong]] (1954) in a medley with [[Tenderly]]\n*[[Mahalia Jackson]]\n*[[Malena Ernman]] (2013)\n*[[Malcolm Vaughan]] (1959)\n*[[Marcus Mumford]] (2020)\n*[[Mark Knopfler]] (2018) incorporated an instrumental version into the track Just a Boy Away From Home on his album [[Down the Road Wherever]]\n*[[Mark Vincent]] (2010)\n*[[Mario Lanza]] (1952 and 1956)\n*[[Maureen Forrester]] on the Carousel MCA Classics album (1987)\n*[[Melanie C|Melanie Chisholm]] (2012)\n*[[Michael Crawford]] (1987)\n*[[Mormon Tabernacle Choir]] (1971)\n*[[Nina Simone]] (1958, ''[[Little Girl Blue (album)|Little Girl Blue]]'')\n*[[Olivia Newton-John]] (1989) \u2013 ''[[Warm and Tender (Olivia Newton-John album)|Warm and Tender]]''\n*[[Patricia Neway]] in the soundtrack of the 1967 television adaptation of ''Carousel'' (1967)\n*[[Patti Labelle & The Blue Belles]] (1964) - US #34\n*[[Patti LaBelle]] (1980's)\n*[[Pink Floyd]] (1971) \u2013 \"[[Fearless (Pink Floyd song)|Fearless]]\"\n*[[Pips, Chips & Videoclips]] (''[[Dernjava]]'' album, 1995)\n*[[The Priests]] (2009)\n*[[Perry Como]] (1951) (with Mitchell Ayres Orchestra)\n*[[Ray Charles]] (''[[Ingredients in a Recipe for Soul]]'' album track, July 1963)\n*[[Regine Velasquez]] (1989)\n*[[Ren\u00e9e Fleming]] (2003)\n*[[The Righteous Brothers]] (1965)\n*[[Riverdale Cast]] featuring main vocals of [[Madelaine Petsch]] (2018), appeared on ''[[Riverdale (2017 TV series)|Riverdale]]'' <ref>https://genius.com/Riverdale-cast-youll-never-walk-alone-lyrics</ref>\n*[[Robin S]] (appears on the 1998 movie soundtrack, ''[[Welcome to Woop Woop]]'')\n*[[Robson & Jerome]] (1996)\n*[[Roy Hamilton]] (1954)<ref name=pc3/>\n*[[Roy Orbison]] (1969) [[Sound recording and reproduction|recorded]] (2015) Released\n*[[Samuel Ramey]] (1989)\n*[[Sergio Franchi]] recorded on 1964 RCA album, ''The Exciting Voice of Sergio Franchi''\n*[[The Shadows]] (''[[Reflection (The Shadows album)|Reflection]]'' album track, 1990)\n*[[Shirley Bassey]] (1962, single B-side to \"Ave Maria\")<ref>''Columbia Catalog Number DB4816\"</ref>\n*[[Shirley Jones]] recorded it on the original movie soundtrack of ''Carousel'' and again on her 1989 album ''[[Silent Strength]]''\n*[[Sissel Kyrkjeb\u00f8]] (2004)\n*[[Smoking Popes]]\n*[[The Soldiers]] (2011)\n*[[Steven Houghton]] (1997) \u2013 ''Steven Houghton''\n*[[Susan Boyle]] (''[[Standing Ovation: The Greatest Songs from the Stage]]'', 2012)\n* Tape Toy (''[[2019-20 Coronavirus outbreak]]'', 2020)\n*[[The Three Tenors]] (''[[The Three Tenors: Paris 1998]]'', 1998)\n*[[Tokyo Ska Paradise Orchestra]] (2009) \u2013 ''Paradise Blue''\n*[[Tom Jones (singer)|Tom Jones]] (1969)\n*[[Trisha Yearwood]] (2016) - ''[[The Passion (U.S. TV special)|The Passion]]''\n*[[Vocal Majority]] (1997) \u2013 ''How Sweet the Sound''\n*[[Wayne Hussey]] and [[Julianne Regan]] (as [[Hussey-Regan]]) (2011) (in support of Liverpool F.C.'s disability charity, [[Respect 4 All]])<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/liverpoolfc#p/u/13/xy8MPNixmgI \"You'll Never Walk Alone\"]. Youtube.com (Liverpool FC's Channel). Retrieved December 27, 2011.</ref>\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|barbra-streisand|youll-never-walk-alone}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Rodgers and Hammerstein}}\n{{Liverpool F.C.}}\n{{Liliom}}\n{{Roy Hamilton}}\n{{The Bachelors}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:You'll Never Walk Alone}}\n[[Category:1945 songs]]\n[[Category:1964 singles]]\n[[Category:1985 singles]]\n[[Category:Songs with music by Richard Rodgers]]\n[[Category:Songs with lyrics by Oscar Hammerstein II]]\n[[Category:Songs from Rodgers and Hammerstein musicals]]\n[[Category:Shirley Jones songs]]\n[[Category:Gerry and the Pacemakers songs]]\n[[Category:Barbra Streisand songs]]\n[[Category:Labelle songs]]\n[[Category:Andy Williams songs]]\n[[Category:Jane Morgan songs]]\n[[Category:Johnny Preston songs]]\n[[Category:Glen Campbell songs]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by George Martin]]\n[[Category:Billboard Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs number-one singles]]\n[[Category:UK Singles Chart number-one singles]]\n[[Category:UK Independent Singles Chart number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Irish Singles Chart number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Liverpool F.C. songs]]\n[[Category:Feyenoord songs]]\n[[Category:Celtic F.C. songs]]\n[[Category:Charity singles]]\n[[Category:Football songs and chants]]\n[[Category:Protest songs]]\n[[Category:Mahalia Jackson songs]]\n[[Category:Roy Hamilton songs]]\n[[Category:Columbia Graphophone Company singles]]\n[[Category:Laurie Records singles]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Scotland]]\n", "name_user": "89.243.118.43", "label": "unsafe", "comment": 